<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Crime Down 30 Percent, Say Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Crime has dropped by 30
percent in downtown Sydney even though one million extra visitors
poured into the city for the Olympic Games, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police, who are saturating the city center with officers 24
hours a day, said every type of crime from assaults to theft was
down.
</P>
<P>
"Crime figures have dropped dramatically which is good news," a
police spokesman said. "We have about one million extra visitors
in the city at the moment and that's a million extra targets."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Expected to Hit Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- After two weeks of beautiful
and sunny weather, rain is expected to hit the Sydney Olympic
Games which open here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Showers are forecast across most Olympic venues for Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday. Games organisers said
contingency plans were in place to deal with rain, including
postponing some events.
</P>
<P>
While Games organisers insisted no sports were likely to be
affected by rain, many events on the day might be influenced by
wet conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Transportation to Face Toughest Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- With most of the 100,000
spectators at the opening ceremony travelling by train and bus,
the Olympic transportation systeam will face its toughest test on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.5 million journeys will be made on the rail network on
Friday when the Games open, and among them, 284,000 are into and
out of Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney CityRail train network is now operation on a 24-hour
Olympic timetable and up to 1,400 spectator buses are running on
13 routes in addition to regular bus services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympics Make Big Money from Coin Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Sydney Olympic Games have made
big money from commemorative coin sales, according to local
reports.
</P>
<P>
Some five million Sydney 2000 coins were sold to the end of
August compared with 2.4 million sold for the entire Atlanta
Olympic Games. That brings the games 131 million Australian
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Acrobats Praised for Excellent Performance in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's First Lady Janet
Museveni Thursday evening praised the debut of a Chinese acrobatic
troupe at the International Conference Center in the capital
Kampala as "very enjoyable and successful".
</P>
<P>
Speaking to audience and artists at the end of the show
presented by Tianjin Acrobatic Troupe, Janet said it is a great
pleasure for her to share with artists the rich oriental culture
of China.
</P>
<P>
She expressed hope that more cultural exchanges like this will
add to the friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The troupe arrived here Tuesday at the invitation of the Uganda
Women's Efforts to Save Orphan Organization. The profit of the
shows will go to orphans in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Meets Freed Hostages From Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
president Nelson Mandela Thursday met at his Johannesburg home
freed hostages Callie and Monique Strydom and their parents, the
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"I'm so happy that you are with us. What a trauma this was to
you, your family and all of us," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Callie and Monique were set free three weeks ago after having
been held hostages for more than four months by a Muslim rebel
group in the Philipino island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the two's return to freedom is bittersweet, as
one of those taken hostage with them, a Filipino dive instructor,
is still being held captive.
</P>
<P>
"I will appeal to the South African government and Libyan
leader Muammar Gadaffi to persuade the rebels to release him. His
wife is pregnant and it is really unfair that they release the
others and not him," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
He thanked Gadaffi for the role he played in securing the two
South Africans' release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Diamond Heist in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Diamonds to the value of
6.5 million rand (about 930,000 U.S. dollars) have been stolen by
four armed robbers from the Diamond Cutting Works in Johannesburg,
police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four robbers with handguns waited for three victims to
arrive at work and took the foreman to the safe where the diamonds
were kept and forced him to unlock the safe, said police spokesman
Willem de Villiers.
</P>
<P>
He said the robbers took about 3000 diamonds, 75 percent of
which already polished and destined for the jewelry market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visiting European MPs Stress Parliamentary Democratic System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Sustaining parliamentary
democratic system is essential for socio-economic development in
Bangladesh, visiting members of European Parliaments said here
Thursday while meeting with Bangladeshi Speaker Humayun Rasheed
Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
Showing interest for exchanging experiences of the Bangladesh
Parliament with European Parliaments, the European MPs said they
wanted to know the systems and procedures of Bangladesh Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Chowdhury explained about allocation of time for both the
Treasury and Opposition bench during discussion, general debates
and other proceedings and programs of the Bangladesh Parliament to
the European guests.
</P>
<P>
Later the MPs handed some books and documents containing the
rules of procedures and secretarial systems of European
Parliaments to the speaker.
</P>
<P>
The three-member European Parliaments delegation arrived here
Thursday for a five-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Killed, Three Wounded in Indian Firing: Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- At least one person was
killed and three others wounded Thursday in Indian firing at the
Pakistan-administered Kashmir, reported the Associated Press of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting local officials, said Indian forces fired
and shelled across the Line of Control, which divides Pakistan and
India in the disputed area of Kashmir, and as a result a resident
of Flakan village in the Neelum valley was killed and his three
sons sustained injuries.
</P>
<P>
The Indian troops used mortar and artillery to hit the innocent
civilians in these areas, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
