<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Lebanon at Odds over Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Troubles seem to appear in
repatriating to Lebanon the 266 illegal immigrants, who were saved
from drowning Wednesday by Cyprus authority when their boat sank
off the western island.
</P>
<P>
The illegal immigrants, mainly Iranians and Kurds, are now on
two Cyprus boats in the Limassol port, on the island's southern
coast.
</P>
<P>
According to local media Friday, Constantin Tabet, Lebanese
charge d'affaires in Nicosia, said that his country would not
accept the immigrants, as the Lebanese authorities have not yet
found the specific boat in its ship register, adding that there was
no evidence that the boat has sailed from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Interior Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou Friday said
he had asked for a Lebanese delegation to visit Cyprus to determine
the facts.
</P>
<P>
He said that the specific boat had sailed from Lebanon for
either Greece or Italy and that the Italian and Greek authorities
had been notified.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou noted that he had given instructions to the
Foreign Ministry to send a representation in writing to the
Lebanese charge d'affaires in Cyprus, accompanied with evidence and
documents.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Lebanon has to take its responsibilities, under an
agreement signed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A bilateral agreement signed between Cyprus and Lebanon last
year made provisions for the return of illegal immigrants if proved
their origin of departure.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou added that until the matter is settled, no illegal
immigrant would be allowed off the two boats they are restricted
on, and that they would all be boarded onto a larger boat, when
they will be ready to depart.
</P>
<P>
Tabet said he would try to convince his government to send a
representative to Cyprus within the next couple of days, to discuss
the problem and make an effort to solve it as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
