<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A majority of Israelis support the sweeping civic
reforms proposed by Prime Minister Ehud Barak, according to a
survey conducted on behalf of the Israeli leading daily The
Jerusalem Post published on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reform proposals polled by the Smith Institute, a long-
established polling company in Israel, included allowing stores in
city centers to remain open, public transportation to operate, and
state-run airline El Al to fly on Shabbat, and permitting civil
marriages.(Israel-Majority-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will incorporate fossil beds found in a village
of southwestern province Mugla in 1993 into a nature park nearby to
establish the second largest outdoor nature museum in the world,
Turkish Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project, under the auspices of the Culture Ministry and the
Mugla Governorship, will be named the Turolian Nature Park 2000.
The nature park will be the world's second largest one with the
first in the U.S. state of Colorado. (Turkey-Nature Park)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli military announced Friday that Major
General Moshe Ya'alon is to be the state's new deputy chief of
staff in place of Major General Uzi Dayan.
</P>
<P>
Ya'alon, named "Boogie", has served in several sensitive posts,
including commander of the elite Sayeret Matkal commando unit,
chief of military intelligence and in his present position, as
General Officer Commanding (GOC) Central Command, which includes
the West Bank. (Israel-New Military Chief)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Former Lebanese army commander General Michel Aoun,
who lives in exile in Paris, said that he was ready to open a
dialogue with Druze Muslim leader Walid Jumblatt, who helped Syria
oust him 10 years ago, the Oriental Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
"Walid Jumblatt is serious in his policy of opening up toward
Christians, and I am ready to begin the talk," Aoun was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Jumblatt, the leader of the Progressive Socialist Party (PSP)
and a big winner in recent parliamentary elections, asked Syrian
President Bashar al-Assad on Wednesday in Damascus to adjust the
Lebanese-Syrian relations in the interests of both countries.
(Lebanon-Aoun-Jumblatt) 
</P>
