<HEADLINE> Ethiopians in New Afforestation Drive to Check Soil Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopians are making use
of the current rainy season to plant millions of trees in their
efforts to check soil erosion, media here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
More than 9.4 million tree seedlings are being transplanted to
different areas in the northern Tigray State, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said the seedlings of acacia, eucalyptus and other tress are
being planted in 10 selected areas with sparse vegetation coverage.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers are participating the program through a "food-for-
work" program sponsored by the government.
</P>
<P>
The country reportedly planted about 10.7 million trees last
season in the region, and some 75 percent of them have survived.
</P>
</TEXT>
