<HEADLINE> Eastern, Southern African Region Has Safe Airspace: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- An official from the
International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) Friday refuted
claims that it is not safe flying in the sky of the eastern and
southern African region.
</P>
<P>
The region has up to standard communication facilities and has
safe airspace, Lambert Ndiwaita, an officer of airdrome and ground
aids with the ICAO Eastern and Southern African region office
based in Nairobi, Kenya, was quoted by media here as saying.
</P>
<P>
Unlike in the past when the region depended on land telephones,
almost all the countries in the region are now using the Vertical
Small Aperture Terminal satellite communication and have very high
frequency omni-directional range, he said while attending a five-
day international workshop on airdrome emergency planning in the
eastern and southern Africa region, which ended here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ndiwaita was reacting to a statement issued earlier by the
South African Pilot Association saying the airspace north of the
Limpopo River, which runs across South Africa, Botswana, Zimbabwe
and Mozambique, is not safe and therefore not worth flying through.
</P>
<P>
"In relation to the air traffic we have in the region, the
facilities available suits the safety purposes, we may need to
increase them in future when we have more traffic," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said there are many issues which should be considered before
establishing whether the airspace or airports are safe or not.
</P>
<P>
These include communication facilities, licensing pilots,
aircrew, air traffic controller authority, certification of air
worthiness inspectors and aviation security, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
