<HEADLINE> Italy's Genoa Starts Organizing for Next July's G8 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Along with the leaders of the world's major powers, the city is
expecting about 10,000 persons to be on hand in various functions
at what is a major media event and showcase.
</P>
<P>
Italian news agency Ansa reported that on Friday the government
's man in charge of organization Achille Vinci Giacchi was in town
to look at the venues chosen for the summit meetings, the Ducal
Palace and the Cotton Warehouses.
</P>
<P>
According to Vinci Giacchi, a diplomat, "to imagine the G8 as
nothing but a meeting of the wealthy is an over-dramatization;
globalization is inevitable, and good for economic development,
but has less favorable aspects that need examination."
</P>
<P>
He also said the first thing would be to show that Genoa is a
welcoming city ready to discuss the issues raised by those wanting
to protest against the G8 and what it represents: "we'll do this
with a series of events we are currently working on. Then we will
have to find the venues needed for those who will be involved."
</P>
