<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- As the water level in dams has fallen to the lowest
level of the last 30 years, Turkey is faced with an energy shortage
of some 6 billion kilowatt hours this year, reported Anatolia News
Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The energy shortage has worsened because the government's energy
plans couldn't be put into effect for the last two and a half
years, according to Yurdakul Yigitguden, undersecretary of the
Energy and Natural Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 29 projects should be put into effect as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The exchange market in Lebanon is stable and the U.S.
dollar exchange rate is fixed at 1,514 Lebanon pounds since early
2000, said Governor of the Central Bank of Lebanon Riad Salame.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no extra interference by the central bank in
the exchange rate and the interest rates are stable as well.
</P>
<P>
The bank's foreign reserves increased from 1 billion U.S.
dollars seven years ago to 7 billion dollars at present, said the
governor.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Central Bank of Morocco announced that its net
foreign reserves shrank from 5.8 billion U.S. dollars at the end of
1999 to 5 billion dollars at the end of July, down by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of dirham will lead to higher prices of the
imported essential commodities, as the case of oil prices,
economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
The problem was triggered by the continued decrease of the
European single currency euro against the U.S. dollar, said a bank
analyst.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The value of Tunisia's exports of phosphate and its
products in the first seven months of 2000 reached 399.3 million
dinars (287.3 million U.S. dollars), up by 4.72 percent from that
of the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The value of Tunisia's imports of phosphate and its products
amounted to 134.1 million dinars (96.47 million dollars), up by 30.
33 percent from that of the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Thus the trade balance registered a surplus of 265.2 million
dinars (190.79 million dollars) compared with a surplus of 280.7
million dinars (200.9 million dollars)in the same period of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
