<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Side Returns to Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides has decided to return to the fourth round of U.N.-
sponsored proximity talks in New York Friday after a two-day
absence, the Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said, through his spokesman, that he is not looking for
excuses to leave the dialogue because such a move would perpetuate
the division of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's statement, issued as the
Cyprus talks opened Tuesday, raised concerns among the Greek
Cypriot side with regard to references stressing the need for
explicit recognition of the equal status of the island's two
Cypriot communities in the comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou, who is also in New
York, said "all unclear references, everything that could have been
exploited by the Turkish side, have been fully annulled and
revoked."
</P>
<P>
He said that Clerides has received assurances, through public
statements and in private, that the negotiations will continue
strictly within the framework of the U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolutions defined political equality not as numerical
equality but sufficient representation in the governance of the
federal state which will emerge from the talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the tiny Mediterranean island in the wake of a
failed coup in Nicosia seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island with
a bicommunal bizonal federation formula, but all efforts have been
so far failed.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks have been held
since last December, in an effort to find a way for a Cyprus
solution. The fourth round of talks are underway in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
