<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Calls for Aid to Continue Landmine Clearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government Friday
appealed to the international community for continued assistance
to help clear the large number of landmines across the country,
Angola's official news agency Angop reported.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the countries in the world with the largest
number of planted landmines. During the 25-year civil war between
the government troops and rebels led by Jonas Savimbi, some 11
million landmines were planted in the country, with a population
of only 12 million.
</P>
<P>
According to Rolando Neto, Angola's delegate to the Second
International Conference on Anti-personnel Landmines currently
held in Geneva, some 15,000 of the mines were already removed
during the period from 1996 to the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
This covered more than 5,000 kilometers of road and 8,000
square kilometers of land, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said despite the efforts and progress made by the
Angolan government in clearing landmines, the bulk of them still
remain underground and there were 1,117 people wounded or killed
during 735 landmine explosions over the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
