<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Sees Palestinian Proposal Not Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel said Friday
that the proposal made by the Palestinian side for Islamic
sovereignty over holy places in Jerusalem did not look promising.
</P>
<P>
Acting Israeli Foreign Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami made the
statement after meeting with Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdullah
Al-Khalil at the United Nations in the morning. It is Israel's
first official reaction to the proposal which Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat put to U.S. President Bill Clinton on September 6.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Ben-Ami said, "It doesn't matter to us
very much if it is Palestinian or Islamic. It's the same, so the
idea doesn't look as a real starter for a solution," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans are interested but we have not yet seen an
Israeli readiness to accept it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said the idea was an alternative to exclusive
Palestinian sovereignty over the holy places, the traditional
demand of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
"We are reviewing all the core issues and looking into the
positions of the other side, and the other side is looking at our
positions. We will see how we proceed," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been trying to mediate a solution to the
Jerusalem dispute. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Middle East envoy Dennis Ross held meetings with the two sides in
New York Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ross will see both sides again Friday and Albright will see the
Palestinian negotiators later in the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
