<HEADLINE> Hunger Hits 13 Percent of World Population: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Undernourishment in populous Asian countries has diminished,
but remains a focus of concern in Africa, the FAO said in its 2000
annual report on the state of food and agriculture, which was
released Friday through the U.N. headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The last years of the 20th century were generally unfavorable
for world food and agriculture with many developing countries
facing adverse climatic conditions, the negative impact of the
1997 financial crisis and political instability and conflicts in a
number of cases, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The FAO blames armed conflicts and civil strife for bringing
food insecurity and agricultural output losses are estimated in
developing countries at 121 billion U.S. dollars over the period
from 1970 to 1997, an average of 4.3 billion dollars per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
