<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicosia Irked by Annan's Statement on Equality of Two Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The political parties in
Cyprus have been expressing their indignation over a statement made
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday in which he
referred to the "political equality" of the two Cypriot sides on
the island.
</P>
<P>
In his statement during separate meetings with Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, Annan
talked about the "equal status" of the two parties on the divided
Mediterranean island, which must be recognized explicitly in a
comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
The statement, made on the first day of the fourth round of U.N.
-sponsored proximity talks, triggered great controversy and kept
Clerides, leader of the Greek Cypriots, away from the talks for
Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the National Council, the top advisory body to the
president on the Cyprus issue, continued Friday its marathon
session in New York on development in the proximity talks.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Democratic Rally party branded Annan's statement as "
unfortunate." And the socialist Kisos Movement said the U.N. chief,
instead of upholding U.N. decisions, sought to "promote
unacceptable Turkish demands, obviously with the encouragement of
the Americans and Britain."
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party's parliamentary spokesman Tassos
Papadopoulos termed the statement as a bad development. He
suggested the Greek Cypriot side ignore Annan's "conclusions" and
continue to cite U.N. resolutions as a basis for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Minister George Iacovou criticized in particular
the reference to the "new partnership" and absence of the word "
communities" in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Political commentators here claimed that it was a clear attempt
by Annan, with the backing of Britain and the Americans, to
introduce confederation on the island.
</P>
<P>
They believed that Annan, by going out of his way to stress that
each Cypriot leader represented his own side and no one else,
appeared to be bowing to the oft-repeated Denktash demand.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island after a failed coup
seeking union with Greece. The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally
declared a republic in northern Cyprus in 1983, which is only
recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-sponsored indirect talks have been held and
the fourth round is underway in New York to pave the way for
substantive negotiations to reach a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
So far the Turkish Cypriot side has been refusing to negotiate
face-to-face with the Greek Cypriot side unless its breakaway
regime is recognized.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side has expressed welcome to Annan's statement,
local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit considered Annan's
statement as a positive step. "So far we have been stressing the
principle that there are two separate states in Cyprus. This fact
gradually began to be accepted," he said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Denktash said Annan's statement "has stolen all my
ideas." 
</P>
</TEXT>
