<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Loans to Fight AIDS in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Directors of the
World Bank has agreed to commit an initial amount of 500 million U.
S. dollars over next three years as part of its approved Multi-
Country HIV/AIDS Program (MAP) for Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued by Zambia country office of
the bank on Friday, the first two countries to benefit from the
program are Ethiopia and Kenya, which will receive 59.7 million
dollars and 50 million dollars respectively in soft loans from the
International Development Association.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the two countries, several other countries including
Zambia have already requested the bank to support their ongoing
response to the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The bank expects many other countries in Sub-Saharan Africa to
seek support under the MAP in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS now poses the paramount threat to the development
in Sub-Saharan Africa. Nearly 25 million Africans are living with
HIV/AIDS, the vast majority of whom are adults, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa accounts for more than 70 percent of all HIV/
AIDS cases globally, and is the only region where women living
with HIV/AIDS outnumber men, it added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 15 million people in Africa have died
of AIDS, with devastating social and economic impact.
</P>
<P>
While imposing an unsustainable and mounting burden on
households, firms and the public sector, the epidemic is costing
the region close to 1 percent of its economic growth each year,
said the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
