<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Reiterates Support for Cyprus Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For Greece and the rest of the international community, the
only legal authority on Cyprus was the Cyprus Republic and no one
would allow the recognition of the Turkish Cypriot regime led by
Rauf Denktash, said Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas at
a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Reppas was referring to the controversial statement made by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday afternoon as the two
communities on Cyprus began their fourth round of the U.N.-
sponsored proximity talks at the U.N. headquarters in New York.
Annan said in his statement that the equal status of the parties
must and should be recognized explicitly in the comprehensive
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Cyprus issue as being in a crucial phase, Reppas
said that Athens backed the efforts of the Cypriot government for
the solution of the Cyprus problem and was waiting for Annan's
response with regard to his statement before it decided its
position.
</P>
<P>
He denied that Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou exerted
pressures on Clerides, who is now hesitating whether Nicosia
should continue such talks with the Turkish Cypriot side or not.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The talks have been deadlocked for many years primarily over
the refusal of Denktash to meet directly with Clerides or to
discuss substantive issues unless northern Cyprus is recognized.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus have insisted that Cyprus must be reunited in
a federation formula in line with the U.N. resolutions, but Turkey
and northern Cyprus demand that a confederation formed by two
sovereign states be set up on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Greece (KKE) has criticized Annan's
statement and urged the Greek government to firmly support
Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Former Greek Defense and Education Minister Gerassimos Arsenis
Friday called on Athens to help Cyprus maintain a firm stance
against multiple pressures.
</P>
<P>
Describing Annan's statement as "provocative and unacceptable,"
Arsenis warned that to accept Annan's recommendation to continue
Cyprus proximity talks on this basis would be extremely dangerous
for the future of Greece in general since legalizing northern
Cyprus would turn Cyprus into a Turkish protectorate and open up
new fronts in the Aegean Sea and the northeastern Greek region of
Thrace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Commends Support of Group of 77 for U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Only with your support can we become the kind of efficient,
well-managed organization," he told the group's annual meeting of
foreign ministers of the Group of 77, being held at the U.N.
headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
With the support, the United Nations can persuade
industrialized nations to open more their markets to developing-
country products, reverse the decline of development aid, cancel
the debts of poor countries and accept a more equitable process
for arbitrating or mediating in disputes between creditors and
debtors, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"Only as an efficient, open and flexible organization can the
United Nations hope to influence the course of globalization," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking high of the April Havana South summit, Annan said that
the recent U.N. Millennium Summit Declaration had reproduced many
points from the Group of 77 Havana Declaration, which focuses on
poverty, disease, violence, transnational crime and environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that "the cry of anguish" of developing countries on
the impact of globalization "did not go unheard."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief congratulated Iran on being elected Friday as
the next chair of the group to replace Nigeria whose term ends in
January.
</P>
<P>
Founded on June 15, 1964 by 77 developing countries at the
first session of the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (
UNCTAD) in Geneva, the group has been expanded to a membership of
133 countries, the largest South grouping to promote collective
economic interests on major economic issues in the U.N. system.
</P>
</TEXT>
