<HEADLINE> Twenty Killed In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Twenty people including 14
so-called militants and three Indian soldiers were killed since
Thursday evening in Kashmir, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted an official spokesman as saying that gunmen
abducted a local leader of the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party,
Ilyas Ahmad Pir, on the outskirts of Srinagar last night and took
him to unknown destination.
</P>
<P>
Four militants were killed in two separate encounters with
local security forces in frontier district of Kupwara Thursday
evening, from whom four AK assault rifles and some ammunition were
recovered, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
An local policeman was killed and another seriously wounded
when militants attacked a police party posted on guard at a shrine
in Baramulla district last night.
</P>
<P>
Two Indian soldiers and a defense committee member in the area
also lost their lives in the encounter, PTI said, adding militants
had triggered a series of blasts enroute to their hideout where
the encounter took place.
</P>
<P>
Indian troops shot dead four militants in Poonch District on
Friday in a gun battle, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the insecurity in the area, authorities in Indian-
controlled Kashmir issued orders Thursday for construction of 1000
household bunkers and 100 community bunkers in the shelling prone
areas of border districts of Baramulla and Kupwara, an official
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the household bunkers would be done at the
cost of 20,000 rupees (near 435 U.S. dollars) by beneficiaries
themselves who would be paid 17,445 rupees (about 380 dollars) in
three installments, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The community bunkers would cost 35000 rupees (760 dollars), he
said, adding that, in all, 50 million rupees (108,700 dollars)
would be spent on the construction of the bunkers in the first
phase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central government alerted all states today to
take suitable security precautions in the wake of intelligence
inputs on the movement of about 100 militants with arms and
explosives from Pakistan to carry out bomb blasts across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Home Affairs asked all state governments to
follow a "strong security drill" against the devious plans of
terrorist groups to target vulnerable places.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the ministry said the ministry had asked the state
government to maintain a "very close and careful eye" on all kinds
of subversive forces through "regular patrolling, surprise checks
and close interaction and coordination among all concerned
agencies" to monitor, check and cross-check all developments and
anticipated events on a strong note of urgency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
