<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Rises 0.3 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial
production increased 0.3 percent in August after revised figures
showed it was flat in July, the Federal Reserve reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Fed estimated one month ago the industrial production
increased 0.4 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output inched up 0.1 percent in both July and
August, a slower rate than in the first half of the year, when
increases in manufacturing production averaged a little more than
0.5 percent per month. Mining output was unchanged in August,
while production at utilities surged 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Capacity utilization for total industry rose 0.1 percentage
point to 82.3 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times since
June 1999 to slow economic growth and keep inflation under control.
A spate of economic reports indicate the Fed's rate increases are
working, leading many economists to predict that the central bank
will avoid raising rates for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
In another report, the Commerce Department said that businesses
' inventories grew by a smaller-than-expected 0.2 percent in July
and sales fell 0.4 percent, the first decline since April, further
evidence of a moderating economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
