<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Directive For Measuring Standardization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Friday that it has adopted a proposal for a directive on measuring
instruments in a bid to ensure consumer protection and improve the
European single market.
</P>
<P>
The European Union's (EU) executive arm said the measuring
instruments are of EU-wide significance. The concerned instruments
include taxi-meters, petrol pump counters, breath-alyzers, water-,
gas- and electricity-meters and automatic weighing instruments
used in production lines for pre-packed products.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner for Enterprise Erkki Liikanen said the draft
has been widely discussed with EU member states, business sectors,
users, consumers and other interested parties.
</P>
<P>
"By guaranteeing certainty of measurement and alignment with
international standards, it opens a large market to manufacturers
in and outside the European Union," he said.
</P>
<P>
Representing a significant simplification, the legal proposal
will replace 11 existing directives and many laws at the national
level.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposal is intended to improve EU's internal market
and to ensure the protection of consumers and trust between
parties in transactions.
</P>
<P>
It will also give manufacturers a choice of conformity
assessment procedures and allow them to fully benefit from
technology progress and international standardization work, the EU
executive said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
