<HEADLINE> Indonesia, UNTAET to Cooperate in Bordering Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government and
the United Nations Transitional Administration in East Timor (
UNTAET) Friday signed an agreement on cooperation to settle the
problems on the border areas between Indonesia and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, called Memorandum of Understanding (MoU), was
signed in Bali, Indonesia, by Indonesian Coordinating Minister for
Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono
and UNTAET Chief Sergio De Millo, reports reaching here Friday
evening said.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the MoU is one of the efforts made by Indonesia,
the UNTAET and all international community to end the problems
taking place along the border areas, especially the refugee
problem in East Nusa Tenggara province, Indonesia," said Susilo.
</P>
<P>
With the aim to coordinate each step among the concerned
parties, especially for Indonesian government to respond to U.N.
Security Council 1319 Resolution, the MoU stipulates that it is a
common responsibility for the Indonesian government, the UNTAET
and other sides to settle the conflicts along the border areas as
well as the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
During the closed-door meeting which was attended by some
Indonesian senior officials and UNTAET chief and East Timorese
leader Xanana Gusmao, Susilo said, the participants also discussed
the refugee issue and held that concrete steps should be taken for
the security along the border area.
</P>
<P>
Many conflicts between U.N. peacekeeping forces in East Timor
and pro-Jakarta East Timorese militiamen have been taken place
along the border areas in recent months, killing and injuring some
U.N. peacekeepers
</P>
<P>
The UNTAET has alleged that intensified activities on the
border was supported by and involved the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
On September 6, a mob of pro-Jakarta East Timorese militia
attacked and burned the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
Office in Atambua, a city of East Nusa Tenggara province of
Indonesia, killing three of the U.N. agency's relief workers.
</P>
<P>
On September 8, the U.N. passed its Resolution No. 1319, urging
the Indonesian government to disarm and disband the militias in
Indonesia. It also urged the Indonesian government to take
measures to end violence in west Timor where 130,000 East Timorese
refugees still remain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
