<HEADLINE> More Efforts Needed for Return of Afghan Refugees: UNHCR Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Ms. Sadako Ogata Friday said
international aid for Afghan refugees has decreased and efforts
should be made to create "sustainable return conditions" for them.
</P>
<P>
There are some 2.6 million Afghan refugees still inhabiting in
Pakistan and Iran and they want to return to their homes, Ogata
told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
"We will explore the possibility for their return home, even to
create those conditions for the repatriation," said the UNHCR
chief.
</P>
<P>
Many Afghan refugees would like to go back but this is not
happening as the conditions in Afghanistan are bad, she said.
</P>
<P>
Ogata urged Pakistan to maintain the compassionate attitude
towards the refugees. "Protect them who need protection," she
added.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR chief is on a tour here which will also take her to
Kabul and Tehran in next couple of days. The basic purpose of her
visit, she said, was to ensure the continued asylum and protection
of Afghan refugees as long as conducive conditions were not
created for their return.
</P>
<P>
Afghan refugee problem is a "very serious issue the
international community should not be inattentive to," said Ogata.
</P>
<P>
To a question, she said, the international community needed
more assurances on the "objectives of Taliban and their policy on
women, education and health. And how they manage the humanitarian
and human rights issue."
</P>
<P>
During her visit to Afghanistan, Ogata said, she will
definitely take up the issue of women with the Taliban authorities.
She said their policy on women was one of the strong causes
hampering their recognition by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Ogata, who arrived here Thursday, held meetings with Pakistan
President Rafiq Tarar and Chief Executive General Pervez Musharraf
earlier Friday to discuss the issue of Afghan refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
