<HEADLINE> Former EU Commissioner Criticizes French Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Former European Commissioner
Karel Van Miert has criticized the French government over its
unilateral solution to truck protesters' demands against rising
fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
Van Miert blamed the French government for causing its European
Union (EU) partners some serious troubles, local press reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was improper for the French government to unilaterally
reduce duty on diesel fuel under pressure from its truck drivers,
he was quoted by the press.
</P>
<P>
The former EU official from Belgium said that France should
have called a meeting of relevant EU ministers instead of caving
in immediately and causing its European partners the widespread
fuel crisis.
</P>
<P>
Noting that France is holding the EU presidency, Van Miert said
the European Commission could have done more such as urging the
French government to take a European initiative though the EU
executive arm has little to say in transport policy.
</P>
<P>
Angry Belgian truckers followed French haulage workers this
week to blockade some majors roads and ports as well as oil depots
in the country to protest the steep rise in fuel prices. They
hoped to gain the same result as French truckers from government
concessions.
</P>
<P>
The country's main employers' federation VBO estimated that the
five-day protests cost Belgium 10 billion Belgian francs (215
million U.S. dollars) daily.
</P>
<P>
The protesters caused traffic chaos and forced several
businesses and schools to close. Emergency services were warned of
serious consequences if the blockades continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
