<HEADLINE> Low-Income Families in Belgium to Get Energy Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian government will
issue energy vouchers to low-income families in a bid to help them
face financial difficulties caused by rising fuel prices, the
local press said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Economic Affairs Charles Picque said the government
has decided to compensate families on the first 1,000 liters of
heating oil purchased. This means all families under a gross
income of 750,000 Belgian francs (16,129 U.S. dollars) will
receive five Belgian francs per liter of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The energy vouchers will be issued in the coming weeks. Some
600,000 Belgian families are expected to benefit from the new
measures.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government has also adopted another measure to help
low-income families. Belgian Social Integration Minister Johan
Vande Lanotte said his ministry is urging all oil companies to
contribute at least one billion Belgian francs (21.5 million
dollars) toward measures to cushion the spiraling price of heating
fuel among low-income households.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the economic affairs minister asked oil companies to
contribute at least 300 million Belgian francs (6.45 million
dollars), which the social integration minister felt was not
enough.
</P>
<P>
Vande Lanotte said oil multinationals have made huge profits,
so the only fair option for them is to make more contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
