<HEADLINE> France to Reinforce Troops in Cote d'Ivoire Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- France will reinforce troops in
the capital of Cote d'Ivoire, Abidjan, reported Agence France-
Presse (AFP) on Friday.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted the French ambassador in Abidjan Francis Lott as
saying that he has informed the leader of Cote d'Ivoire's military
junta, General Robert Guei, of France's plan to reinforce troops
in Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
Lott said that the reinforcement is "nothing particular" and
conforms to the French-Ivoirian agreements on defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The number of French troops stationed in the city will increase
from 510 to 680, according to the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The move is apparently connected with Cote d'Ivoire's
presidential election next month, during which conflicts could
take place between the supporters of the junta and the oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Relations between France and Cote d'Ivoire were strained
recently after France asked General Guei not to run for the
presidency while letting all the oppositions join the election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The military junta came to power in last December in a coup
d'etat which overthrew President Henri Konan Bedie.
</P>
<P>
Bedie, who is living in exile in Paris, said last month that he
will return to his country as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 French nationals are living in Cote d'Ivoire, most
of them in Abidjan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
