<HEADLINE> Canada Moves to Toughen Anti-gang Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada is moving to toughen
anti-gang laws and give police special powers to combat organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
Federal Justice Minister Anne McLellan told reporters in
Calcary Thursday that she has asked her deputy minister to invite
Quebec officials for urgent discussions on the province's proposal
that the notwithstanding clause in the Constitution be invoked
against gang violence.
</P>
<P>
The minister said she wants to "make sure we have the
legislation, the law enforcement and the resources necessary to
break the back of organized crime in this country."
</P>
<P>
McLellan was responding to mounting calls for action following
Wednesday's assassination attempt at Montreal crime reporter
Michel Auger, who was shot five times but survived the hail of
bullets.
</P>
<P>
The veteran journalist is reported in stable condition in
hospital after undergoing surgery to remove the bullets from his
body.
</P>
<P>
"It could be bikers or the Mafia or another criminal gang,"
said a colleague working with Le Journal de Montreal.
</P>
<P>
McLellan reaffirmed the country's determination to crack down
on organized crime after Monday's meeting of federal, provincial
and territorial justice ministers, who decided to create a
steering committee of deputy ministers to combat crime gangs.
</P>
