<HEADLINE> Czech GDP Grows 3.1 Percent in First Half of 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic's gross
domestic product (GDP) rose by 3.1 percent in the first half of
this year, demonstrating a trend of continuing economic recovery,
the Czech Statistical Bureau said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the second quarter was slightly higher than the
expected 1.9 percent, but much lower than the growth of 4.4
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The growth was primarily a result of rising domestic demand,
the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau said all indicators showed that the
country's economy was growing and it might raise its forecast for
the country's GDP growth from 2.0 percent to 2.5 percent for the
full year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund last month estimated that the
Czech Republic's GDP would grow 2.0-2.5 percent this year, much
higher than the 1.5-2.0 percent it predicted in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
