<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Finance Minister Defends Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Economy,
Finance and Industry Laurent Fabius on Friday defended the role
played by the euro since its launching last year while expressing
his concern about the turbulence in the exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on the single currency published Friday, Fabius
said that France, which holds the rotating presidency of the
European Union, is concerned by "the present turbulence in the
markets" of exchange.
</P>
<P>
"In Versailles, a very clear message has been sent. This
message has not lost its validity," he said in reference to the
communique by the finance ministers of the 11 euro zone countries
last weekend in Versailles outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers said that they were ready to intervene in
the market to support the euro at any moment.
</P>
<P>
Fabius also said that people should not doubt that euro "has
been a success" since its launching in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It has played the role of protecting shield against the
monetary turbulence linked with the crises in Asia and Russia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the interest rates in Europe are lower
than in the United States because of the euro.
</P>
<P>
"How can we not make a linkage between the existence of the
euro and the growth which the euro zone is experiencing at this
moment? " said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The euro has fallen nearly 30 percent in its exchange rate with
the U.S. dollar since January 1999 and the currency dropped to its
lowest this week, raising doubts about the future of the European
monetary union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
