<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD, ICC in Collaboration on Investment in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) and the International Chamber of
Commerce (ICC) have launched a joint project to help address some
of the difficulties faced by the least developed countries in
attracting foreign investment, said an UNCTAD press release here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique will be one of the five countries participating in
the pilot phase of the UNCTAD-ICC project, according to the press
release.
</P>
<P>
The first workshop was inaugurated on Thursday in the
Mozambican capital of Maputo. The others are Ethiopia, Mali,
Bangladesh and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In Mozambique, as in the other participating countries, the
project has two objectives: to prepare a guide to the country for
foreign investors and to help strengthen the capacity of local
institutions to attract ad retain foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Five donor countries have thus far contributed to the project
as a whole. UNCTAD and ICC note that contributors to the project
include two developing countries: China and India. The other three
donor countries are Finland, France and Norway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
