<HEADLINE> Trial of Boat Accident Suspects Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The trial of four suspects
allegedly responsible for the boat accident that killed 130 people
on June 22 on the Yangtze River near Hejiang in southwest China's
Sichuan Province started today in a local court.
</P>
<P>
The four suspects are identified as Liang Yingjin, owner of the
vessel involved in the accident; Zhou Shoujin, the ship's captain;
Liang Rubing, who was responsible for the ship's safety; and the
ship's conductor, Shi Ping.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 family members of the victims, survivors and
journalists witnessed the hearing in the People's Court of Hejiang
County.
</P>
<P>
The 200-plus family members have sued the suspects for 7.15
million yuan in civil responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
The four also faced criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is expected to last two days, according to court
sources. 
</P>
