<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Must Improve Its Ability to Innovate: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore must improve its
ability to innovate so as to stay ahead in the global league of
the New Economy, Minister of State for Communications and
Information Technology Lim Swee Say said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the e-NNOVATOR Awards 2000, Lee cited that in the
World Economic Forum's latest global competitiveness report,
though Singapore came in first in technology transfer, it was
ranked only 14th in its ability to innovate.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said Singapore need to quicken the pace of
innovation and broaden the base of innovators to become an
innovative economy and society.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Singapore has been promoting innovation in
the private sector, public sector and in schools.
</P>
<P>
Since the launch of the Innovation Development Scheme in 1995,
the government has awarded 480 million Singapore dollars (about
277 million U.S. dollar) worth of development grants to 490
companies, out of which 360 are local companies, Lim said.
</P>
<P>
These grants were used to support 636 innovation development
projects at a total development cost of 2.1 billion Singapore
dollars (about 1.12 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Moreover, another 1.4 billion Singapore dollars (about 809
million U.S. dollars) grants were granted to support more than 150
research and development projects worth 6.5 billion Singapore
dollars (about 3.78 billion Singapore dollars) in total research
spending.
</P>
<P>
The outcomes are encouraging, he said.
</P>
<P>
The commercialization of products and services has more than
doubled within two years from 6.4 billion Singapore dollars (about
3.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 to 13.4 billion Singapore
dollars (about 7.75 billion Singapore dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The number of patents filed in Singapore is on the rise too,
increasing at a rate of 29 percent a year from 1995 to 1999, he
said.
</P>
<P>
With these figures, Lim concluded that private-public sector
partnership goes a long way in helping to promote innovation in
Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver Recovers, Gold Steady in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Prices of silver recovered
on the bullion market in Mumbai (Bombay) Friday on fresh demand
from industrial users, while gold continued to rule steady in the
absence of market-moving factors.
</P>
<P>
Ready silver (.999 fineness) recovered by 15 rupees (0.33 U.S.
dollar) to close at 8,010 rupees (178.00 dollars) per kilogram
from 7,995 rupees (177.67 dollars) previously,
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness) also moved up by 25 rupees (0.56
dollar) to 7,885 rupees (175.22 dollars) per kg. from 7,860 rupees
(174.66 dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, standard gold and twenty-two-carat gold both ruled
steady at 4,490 rupees (99.78 dollars) per 10 grams and 4,155
rupees (92.33 dollars) respectively. 
</P>
