<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Congress Party Admits Membership Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Indian Congress party
admitted on Friday that its membership had come down by half in
tentative figures ahead of a crucial party polls but dismissed
suggestions that it was the result of Sonia Gandhi's leadership.
</P>
<P>
The number of primary members had come down by more than half
from 45.6 million to 22 million, Chairman of Congress Central
Election Authority Ram Niwas Mirdha told the media here.
</P>
<P>
But Mirdha said these were only "tentative" figures and
information from some of the states was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
While membership increased only in three states -- Maharashtra
to the west, Punjab to the northwest and Rajasthan at the center,
it had fallen by half or more in Bihar, Gujarat and Kerala.
</P>
<P>
However, Mirdha indicated the figures was more believable as
the current enrollment drive was "much more genuine" than the ones
earlier during which the number of members was "bloated".
</P>
<P>
According to the Congress official, one of the reasons for the
depleted membership was the new provision under which members have
to pay three years fee and active members have to subscribe to the
party journal "Congress Sandesh". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
