<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Releases Telecoms Competition Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Infocomm Development
Authority of Singapore (IDA) Friday released the Code of Practice
for Competition in the country's telecoms sector.
</P>
<P>
The competition code, to be effective on September 29 this year,
seeks to define the boundaries for the conduct of competition in a
fully liberalized telecommunications environment, IDA said.
</P>
<P>
Its objective is to identify the appropriate regulatory regime
conducive to the development of a competitive market place.
</P>
<P>
The Code comprises ten sections, addressing aspects relating to
the regulatory regime in a competitive environment, IDA said.
</P>
<P>
In particular, IDA elaborated, section two defines what
constitute a dominant licensee in the competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
Another major component of the Code is the facilitation of
interconnection and access arrangements between dominant and non-
dominant licensees.
</P>
<P>
It also allows for licensees to engage in voluntary
interconnection negotiations, and dispute resolution process
exists should the licensees fail to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Code strives to set clear boundaries for competitive market
behavior while providing enough space for innovation and rapid
response to the demands of the market.
</P>
<P>
IDA said the Code will be reviewed within three years to ensure
its continued relevance as the market evolves.
</P>
<P>
Singapore fully liberalized its telecommunications sector on
April 1, 2000, expediting by two years an earlier plan, which had
set the freeing-up date on April 1, 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Retail Sales Drop Marginally in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's overall retail
sales in July this decreased marginally by 0.4 percent over a
month ago, the Singapore Department of Statistics (SDS) said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Retail activities which registered lower earnings in July 2000
included medical goods and toiletries, recreational goods and
department stores.
</P>
<P>
Sales of motor and telecommunications and computers also
declined by 3.5 and 4.1 percent respectively in July this year.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, turnover of furniture and household equipment,
apparel and footwear, food and beverages and optical goods and
books surged by 12.8, 11.3, 9.9 and 9.8 percent respectively in
July this year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with July 1999, retail sales soared by 28.0 percent in
July 2000, due largely to the 68.3 percent growth in motor
vehicles sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
