<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Group Founder to Face Criminal Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Daewoo Group's
former Chairman Kim Woo-choong and 40 senior executives will soon
be charged with their alleged window-dressing of financial
statements for the bankrupt conglomerate, South Korea's Financial
Supervisory Commission (FSC) said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
FSC said it has decided to file a criminal complaint against
Kim and the 40 executives after a month-long special audit of the
bankrupt Daewoo Group, once the second largest conglomerate in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
FSC will soon file the complaint with the Seoul District
Prosecutor's Office against former Daewoo executives on suspicion
of having fabricated settlements amounting to 22.9 trillion won (
some two billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 40 executives include former Daewoo Motor Presidents Kim
Tae-gou and Kim Shin-chung, former Daewoo Corporation President
Shin Young-kyun and other former and current senior managers.
</P>
<P>
Citing the special audit results of Daewoo Group, FSC said that
equity capital of 12 Daewoo affiliates as of August last year
turned out to be minus 28.6 trillion won as a result of due
diligence, a stark disparity with the 14.3 trillion won reported
by Daewoo to the South Korean government.
</P>
<P>
In terms of subsidiary companies, Daewoo Corporation was found
to actively inflate its assets by 14.6 trillion won, followed by
Daewoo Motor with 3.2 trillion won, Daewoo Heavy Industries with 2.
1 trillion won, Daewoo Electronics with 2 trillion won and Daewoo
Telecom with 600 billion won.
</P>
<P>
Window-dressing settlements were made in various forms of
omitting debts, summing up bad bonds and adding false cost of
research and development on their balance sheets, said FSC.
</P>
<P>
The financial regulator will also request the prosecutor's
office to investigate 11 public accounts involved in the Daewoo
case and cancel the registration of 22 public accountants and
suspend 19 others from doing business.
</P>
<P>
Accountants found to be involved in the illicit practice will
also face punitive measures, including cancellation of their
licenses, added FSC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
