<HEADLINE> Israel Names New Deputy Military Chief of Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli military
announced Friday that Major General Moshe Ya'alon is to be the
state's new deputy chief of staff in place of Major General Uzi
Dayan.
</P>
<P>
Ya'alon, named "Boogie", has served in several sensitive posts,
including commander of the elite Sayeret Matkal commando unit,
chief of military intelligence and in his present position, as
General Officer Commanding (GOC) Central Command, which includes
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Dayan stepped down Friday and is to take his new post on
September 28 as Prime Minister Ehud Barak's military advisor and
head of the National Security Council, which is charged with
reviewing military policy and defense strategy and reporting to the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who is also the Defense Minister, said on Friday at a
closed handover ceremony for the deputy chief of staff that he
received the green light from Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein
to name Dayan head of the National Security Council while retaining
his military rank, said Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Barak was reacting to criticism from the Israeli Defense Forces
(IDF) Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz that Dayan should have taken the
post as a civilian.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, Mofaz sharply criticized both Barak and
Dayan. He also accused Dayan of not keeping understandings reached
regarding when he would leave the post and of creating tensions
that made working together difficult.
</P>
<P>
Dayan responded to Mofaz's criticism, saying respect for fellow
men begins at home. By taking the job and remaining in the army,
Dayan can still be in the running for the next IDF Chief of Staff
appointment.
</P>
<P>
Ya'alon and Dayan are the top candidates to succeed Mofaz as
chief of staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
