<HEADLINE> Exiled Aoun Ready for Talks With Jumblatt on Lebanese Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Lebanese army commander
General Michel Aoun, who lives in exile in Paris, said that he was
ready to open a dialogue with Druze Muslim leader Walid Jumblatt,
who helped Syria oust him 10 years ago, the Oriental Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Walid Jumblatt is serious in his policy of opening up toward
Christians, and I am ready to begin the talk," Aoun was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Jumblatt, the leader of the Progressive Socialist Party (PSP)
and a big winner in recent parliamentary elections, asked Syrian
President Bashar al-Assad on Wednesday in Damascus to adjust the
Lebanese-Syrian relations in the interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
He also called for "strengthening Lebanese national
understanding through dialogue with the representatives of the
Lebanese forces," according to an official from his press office.
</P>
<P>
Jumblatt will go to Paris over the weekend and may meet Aoun,
the radio quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aoun said that he "was ready to go part or even all the way if
necessary" to reach a national understanding.
</P>
<P>
During the recent election campaign, Jumblatt adopted a position
of
openness toward Christian forces. Jumblatt also called on Aoun to
return to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Aoun was driven out of the Presidential Palace in 1990 by
combined Syrian and Lebanese forces and "banished" the same year
for five years. Since then he has not return to Lebanon, for fear
of being prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Aoun had refused to be a part to the Taif Accord which ended the
Lebanese civil war in 1990 because he termed the accord as
legitimizing Syria's military presence in Lebanon. So far, about
35,000 Syrian troops remain in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
