<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Negotiation Efforts to Free Sulu Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States gave its
full support Friday to the Philippine government to resolve
peacefully the Sulu hostage crisis that will lead to the safe
release of all 19 captives held by the extremist Abu Sayyaf group.
</P>
<P>
This was the statement issued by visiting U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen during a joint press conference with his
Philippine counterpart Orlando Mercado here in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Right now the Philippines is facing some difficult internal
challenges on terrorism (and) secessionists in the south," Cohen
said, "the United States strongly supports President Estrada's
effort and his government to secure the prompt and safe release of
American hostage currently being held as well as the other
hostages."
</P>
<P>
Cohen's statement came in the midst of mounting calls from
various sectors for the Philippine government to launch military
strike to rescue the hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
The American defense secretary declined to answer the question
on the military option to resolve the long-drawn hostage crisis,
saying that the United States was hoping "the situation can be
handled diplomatically and the hostages can be safely returned."
</P>
<P>
But he said that decision is "a matter of the (Philippine)
government to decide."
</P>
<P>
In the current hostage crisis, American Jeffrey Schilling is
one of the 19 hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf. Besides, the Abu
Sayyaf group is still holding hostage one Filipino snatched from
Malaysia's Sipadan island, two French journalists, 12 local
Filipino evangelists and three Malaysians newly abducted from
Malaysia's Pandanan island.
</P>
<P>
According to Cohen, Schilling "should be released immediately
and safely and that is something we demand."
</P>
<P>
During the press conference, Secretary Mercado maintained that
the government will continue to seek the release of the 19
hostages through persuasion and negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Philippines has asked the United States to help
rescue the hostages, Mercado replied that he was "not at liberty
to indicate to you what the specifics are if at all there are
discussions between our military establishment and the United
States." 
</P>
</TEXT>
