<HEADLINE> Udinese's Brazilian Duo Lose EU Status in Passport Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Udinese have informed the
Italian Football League that two Brazilian team members caught in
possession of fake Portuguese passports should no longer be
considered European Union (EU) players.
</P>
<P>
Udinese's Warley and Alberto were found to be holding fake
Portuguese passports on arrival in Poland for a UEFA Cup first
round match with Polonia Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
Serie A clubs are limited to five non-EU players, of whom only
three can be on the pitch at the same time. A number of foreign
players bypass the rules by obtaining EU passports through family
history.
</P>
<P>
Udinese general manager Pier Paulo Marino said: "We informed
the league on Thursday that Alberto and Warley should be
considered as non-EU players."
</P>
<P>
Warley and Alberto were detained briefly at Warsaw airport but
were given temporary permission to enter the country for the match
after producing Brazilian passports.
</P>
<P>
Mario said Udinese would investigate the matter thoroughly and
believed the players carried the false passports unwittingly.
</P>
<P>
Lazio's Argentine midfielder Juan Veron recently had his status
as a non-EU player revoked after being accused last season of
wrongfully obtaining an Italian passport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
