<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Ceremony Illustrates History of Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The opening ceremony of the
Millennium Olympics is a celebration of Australia that began by
the sea, and returns to the harbour city after a journey through
the land and history.
</P>
<P>
The audience were taken on a journey through Australian history,
environment and culture by two characters, a little girl and the
traditional Aboriginal dancer Djakapurra.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that an Olympic Opening Ceremony has had
characters that reappeared in each segment, threading the ceremony
together into a whole.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony bursted into life when 120 stockmen on horses
thundered into the arena. They threw their hats into the crowd
and shot the time honoured Australian greeting "G'day".
</P>
<P>
The little girl walked to the center of the arena, spreaded out
a towel, put zinc cream on her nose, lay down and begun to dream
about Australia. She dreamed of the deep blue ocean, of jellyfish,
singrays and other sea creatures.
</P>
<P>
Her dream gave way Djakapurra, Aboriginal dancers and members
of tribes from all corners of the country, who formed circles
around burning eucalyptus leaves. They conjured a giant Wandjina,
a creation myth spirit symbolising the unity of indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
Firebreathers ignited the bush, regeneating the plants that
bloomed into a rippling sea of Australian wildflowers, trees and
animals. Djakapurra walked through the garden and found the
little girl hidden behind a flower.
</P>
<P>
Fire is a significant feature of the Australian landscape. It
was used by Aboriginal peoples to regenerate the bush, and the
great bushfires that can burn uncontrolled across the landscape
are a recuriing natural disaster, that has helped Australians'
relationship with the land.
</P>
<P>
A three person cycle peddled into the arena. At the center it
stopped to begin a segment that takes us on a journey through
enrly Europeana settlement, the struggle to open up and farm the
land, and on to the Australian suburban dream.
</P>
<P>
This is the cue for a series of groups to sweep into the arena.
They represented the successive waves of immigration, that has
transformed Australia into the cosmopolitan and diverse society it
is today.
</P>
<P>
With 2,000 poeple in the center of the arena, Sydney's landmark
Anzac Bridge rose, and Djakapurra and the little girl met again
amid a crescendo that celebrated the city of Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The Syndey 2000 Olympic Band heralded the arrival of the Parade
of Athletes.
</P>
<P>
Once the athletes were assembled, a huge Olympic flag was
passed over the crowd from the southern grandstand as Vanessa
Amorosi performed "Heroes Live Forever". The official Olympic
Flag was then raised.
</P>
<P>
As the Olympic Torch entered the stadium, Tina Arena performed
"The Flame". Once alight, the Cauldron flame is five meters high
and three meters wide, clearly visible outside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
The Opening Ceremony concluded with a spectacular display of
fireworks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
