<HEADLINE> Highlights of Aboriginal Heroine Cathy Freeman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Aboriginal heorine Cathy
Freeman lighted the cauldron of the Millennium Olympic Games here
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Following are the highlights of Cathy Freeman:
</P>
<P>
Date of Birth: February 16, 1973
</P>
<P>
Height: 163 centimeters
</P>
<P>
Past performances:
</P>
<P>
1st: 400m, 49.67 seconds, World Championships in Seville, Spain,
1999
</P>
<P>
1st: 400m, World Championships, in Athens, Greece, 1997
</P>
<P>
2nd: 400m, 48.63 seconds, Olympics, Atlanta, United States,
1996
</P>
<P>
3rd: 4x400m relay, World Championships, in Gothenburg, Sweden,
1995
</P>
<P>
1st: 200m, Commonwealth Games, in Victoria, Canada, 1994
</P>
<P>
1st: 400m, Commonwealth Games, in Victoria, Canada, 1994
</P>
<P>
2nd: 4x100m relay, in Commonwealth Games, in Victoria, Canada,
1994
</P>
<P>
Semifinalist: 200m, World Championships, in Stuttgart, Germany,
1993
</P>
<P>
Quarterfinalist: 400m, Olympic Games, in Barcelona, Spain, 1992
</P>
<P>
2nd: 200m, World Junior Championships, in 1992
</P>
<P>
1st: 4x100m relay, Commonwealth Games, in Auckland, New Zealand,
1990.
</P>
<P>
Highlights:
</P>
<P>
World leader in 2000 at 400m. World 400m champion in 1997 and
1999. At her third Olympics, she is looking to improve on her
silver from Atlanta. Unbeaten in 1999 and 2000 over 400m.
</P>
<P>
Won at Gateshead in August defeating World Champion Inger
Miller over 200m raising the possibility of a 200m/400m double as
she did at Commonwealth Games in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Australia's best individual hope for gold and backbone of
Australia's highly rated 4x400m team.
</P>
<P>
Hobby: Reading. Her favorite books include a biography on the
composer Leonard Bernstein and Chuck Close, an American
photorealist.
</P>
<P>
Injuries: A stress fracture in Europe in 1998 ended her season.
</P>
<P>
Awards and honours: Received the 1999 "Young Australian of the
Year" award. 1991 Aboriginal Athlete of the Year, 1996 Australian
Sports Personality of the Year.
</P>
<P>
For her cultural and athletic accomplishments in 1997, she was
named Australian of the Year, one of the country's highest
civilian honours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
