<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birch, Hero behind Sydney Olympics Opening Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Only when the Sydney Olympics
Games opening ceremony finished could director Ric Birch relieve
for the spectacular extravaganza which he had been planning for
more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
The lighting of the cauldron has been an icing on the cake in
the ceremony and it is the most tightly kept secret. Birch
revealed that the very first idea came to him in Monte Carlo, when
Sydney was announced as the host city for 2000. "It's been refined
since then, but the basic design is still there," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony finishes, Birch added:"Times change, but
this has to be an expression of the host city, and must reflect
its culture, and it must reflect it in Sydney in 2000. I think
we've done that."
</P>
<P>
Birch thought that it could be impossible to hold any ceremony
bigger than this one. "I don't think the ceremonies can get much
bigger - I think Sydney is just about the limit. We were only
able to attempt this ceremony at this complexity because we were
involved in the design of the stadium - it would be impossible to
conduct this in an existing stadium," he said.
</P>
<P>
Having already been involved with the Olympic Games ceremonies
of Los Angeles in 1984 and Barcelona in 1992, Birch has plenty of
experience, but Sydney is the stage of his ultimate production.
</P>
<P>
Birch worked with the architects and was able to incorporate
features including the ring road on ground level, the size of the
entrances, technology, even the position of the cauldron into the
blueprint. This meant wonderful stage props of large dimensions
were easily able to enter and exit the field.
</P>
<P>
Technology advancements have made a huge impact on the Opening
Ceremonies and pushed them to a grand scale, not only with effects,
lighting and sound, but with behind the scene organisation.
</P>
<P>
"The productivity of computers has enabled us to be more and
more ambitious and more and more complex every four years.
</P>
<P>
"In Los Angeles in 1984 we just started using computers,
especially with the lighting and the database for the performers.
Now, even the cauldron itself has extraordinary computer
technology. The production coordination is enormously complex;
we've got nearly 13,000 performers, 6,000 backstage people, close
to 12,000 athletes and officials, -- just to coordinate that
number of people requires computers or years and years and years
of typewriters," Birch said.
</P>
<P>
Of all the elements of the Opening Ceremony, Birch believed
it's the cauldron that is the strongest symbol for the world. "The
ceremony itself is the curtain raiser to the overture of the stars
coming onto the field, and the cauldron represents the athletes."
</P>
<P>
"When the cauldron is alight, that is the symbol to the rest of
the world that the Olympic Games have truly begun," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baumann Tries Again for Doping-Panel Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Dieter Baumann of Germany left
training camp near Brisbane on Friday night to Sydney in another
attempt to give evidence to a panel examining doping charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
The arbitration panel of the world governing athletics body
IAAF, was due to resume discussion of the Baumann case on Saturday
for the third day and decide whether he should be allowed to
compete at the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time within 48 hours that Baumann, 35, has
broken off training in an attempt to gain a hearing before the
panel. The panel has already turned down requests to be heard from
both the athlete himself and from the German athletics
organisation, DLV.
</P>
<P>
Another DLV submission that the panel was not empowered to deal
with the case was also unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
A mood of pessimism was meanwhile spreading in the German
Olympic team with DLV official Clemens Prokop saying: "This is
certainly not a good sign."
</P>
<P>
Baumann himself said Friday before leaving Brisbane that events
were not happening as he had envisaged. But he observed
philosophically: "However, that is what often happens in life."
</P>
<P>
Baumann, 35, 5,000 meters winner at the Olympic Games in
Barcelona in 1992, was last autumn twice tested positive for the
banned anabolic steroid nandrolone but was cleared after
convincing prosecutors and the DLV that he was the victim of a
conspiracy. He said his toothpaste had been spiked.
</P>
<P>
But the IAAF has the final say and the IAAF council in July
referred the case to its arbitration panel for a final ruling.
</P>
<P>
If the arbitration panel rules that Baumann violated doping
regulations, he faces a two-year suspension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skeleton Found in Beijing Ancient Tomb Was Female </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The skeleton discovered in a
2,000-year-old tomb in the western part of Beijing was of a woman
who was approximately 160 centimeters tall and 30 years of age.
</P>
<P>
This was just revealed by archaeologists who have been
excavating the ancient tomb for about eight months now.
</P>
<P>
The skeleton was discovered in the front chamber, or the
sitting room of the occupant of the tomb, in July.
</P>
<P>
It was difficult for archaeologists to identify the gender of
the skeleton since parts of the chest, waist and pelvis have
decayed.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists cleaned and fixed the pieces together and x-
rayed the bones after they moved the skeleton piece by piece into
the lab.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have not yet been able to identify the skeleton
or how long it had been buried. The occupant of the tomb is still
unknown since the coffin is yet to be opened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
