<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tensions High in Israeli Arab Sector Over Barakei Inquiry By Qi Deliang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Tensions are running high
among the Israeli Arab population following Attorney General
Elyakim Rubinstein's decision to let the police launch its inquiry
against Hadash (Communist) Party leader Momammed Barakei.
</P>
<P>
Barakei, an Arab member of the Knesset (parliament), was charged
by police for incitement against the law enforcing police.
</P>
<P>
Police said that on September 4, Barakei came to a site in Umm
Al-Faham, an Arab town in northern Israel where illegally built
houses were being demolished, gave a speech to residents watching
the demolition and urged them to take actions against the police if
they demolish their houses again in the future.
</P>
<P>
As asked by the Police, Rubinstein on Wednesday decided to give
the police a green light to investigate Barakei on "suspicion that
he incited violence against the police and encouraged Israeli Arabs
in northern Israel to take actions to protect their homes."
</P>
<P>
Following Rubinstern's decision, Israeli Arab leaders, including
the Monitoring Committee of Arab Leadership, have called several
meetings to decide what actions that Arabs will take to protect
themselves and against the police inquiry.
</P>
<P>
While denouncing Rubinstein's decision, the committee decided to
call for mass demonstrations wherever Barakei is called for
questioning by the police.
</P>
<P>
The committee also called for the dismissal of northern region
police chief Alik Ron, who was at odds with local Arabs, for his
statement on Tuesday that police wanted to launch the investigation
against Barakei.
</P>
<P>
Barakei, elected by the Israeli Arabs of northern Galilee during
the 1999 elections, was not alone in his fight against the planned
police inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Malik Dehamshe, leader of the United Arab List which has
five members in the Knesset, has voiced this total support for
Barakei. Dehamshe said on Thursday that if the policemen try to
demolish Arab homes and break the legs and arms of those trying to
prevent them, the later have the right to do the same.
</P>
<P>
The population of Israeli Arabs has been increasing very fast in
recent years and it stood at around 1.1 Million till now and most
of them are living in northern Israel. Israel's total population
was 6.3 million by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Arabs blamed the government for not paying enough
attention to their social and welfare problems and said they did
not receive equal treatment compared to the Jewish communities.
</P>
<P>
Local Arab Councils, which oversee the development of the Arab
towns and villages, told the government long time ago that they
have run out of money due to less allocations from the government
authorities.
</P>
<P>
It will be difficult for Rubsintern and police to press criminal
charges against Barakei and other Arab Knesset members because
parliamentary immunity for speeches can not be stripped under any
circumstances, and the police investigation against Barakei would
add more fire to the existing tensions among the Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
To ease this tension, President Moshe Katsav called on Arab
leaders on Thursday and told them he will offer his assistance to
help solve some problem facing the Arab sector.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Thursday that the Israeli
Arabs are "loyal citizens" and promised to work to improve their
social and welfare status.
</P>
<P>
No matter how the police will conduct investigation against
Barakei, the problem of demolition of Arab homes built without the
so-called permits needs the government to address too.
</P>
<P>
"One of the main reasons that (Arab) people are forced to build
homes without permits is because municipal zoning plans are either
non-existent or so out of date that they do not relate to the needs
of our communities," Mohammed Zeidan, Chairmen of the Monitoring
Committee of Arab Leadership stated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The atmosphere in the Arab communities is extremely tense and
all members of the monitoring committee fully support Barakei,
because the demolition of homes is an extremely sensitive issue on
which all Arab leaders are united," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners To Pay Entry Fee To Indian Monuments In Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Archaeological Survey of
India (ASI), which is in charge of ancient site maintenance in the
country, decided to raise entrance fee to monuments and charge
foreign visitors in U.S. dollars, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The entrance fee would be increased to 10 rupees (near 0.22 U.S.
dollars) from the existing 5 rupees (0.11 dollars) for domestic
tourists while foreigners would have to pay 10 dollars instead of
current level of 5 dollars, PTI quoted ASI Direct General Komal
Anand as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to PTI, Anand said in Agra, an ancient city 200
kilometers southeast of here, that a national culture fund would
be set up for the better maintenance of national monuments.
</P>
<P>
The fund would be used for reservation and refurbishment of the
monuments, Anand said. However, she did not specify when the new
rates would come into force.
</P>
<P>
The new rules would make visit little cheaper for foreign
tourists to the famous Taj Mahal, one of the seven wonders in the
world, as Agra Development Authority is now charging 500 rupees (
some 11 dollars) from them as road tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
