<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Electoral Body Urged to Act Tough Against Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar's ruling Chama
Cha Mapinduzi (CCM) party has asked the Zanzibar Electoral
Commission (ZEC) to act tough against acts of violence and
hooliganism in the run-up to the general elections to be held on
October 29, the official Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday, the CCM claimed that acts of
hooliganism being practiced by the opposition Civic United Front (
CUF) supporters are a threat to peace and political stability in
the Indian Ocean Isles.
</P>
<P>
It further said the CUF's violence was a special ploy designed
to disrupt peace and create an environment of fear, which will
make the October elections not "free and fair".
</P>
<P>
The party urged ZEC to condemn the acts and take concrete steps
to control the situation before it gets out of hand, citing recent
illegal demonstrations and a stone throwing incident which took
place last weekend and left six people injured .
</P>
<P>
The ZEC said on Tuesday it was about to hold a joint meeting
with police officers and representatives of all political parties
taking part in next month's elections to discuss ways of
controlling the increasing violence.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. But with its own government and
parliament, it is a semi-autonomous region in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
It will go to polls simultaneously with the mainland in the
second multi-party elections this year, choosing its own president
as well as a new leader of the Union government.
</P>
</TEXT>
