<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Flights to Central Angolan Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Humanitarian aid flights for
war-displaced Angolans in the country's central coastal Benguela
province have been resumed recently after a 50-day suspension, the
official Angolan news agency Angop reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of flights to this region will secure food
assistance for over 16,000 displaced persons and thousands of
local residents, according to the humanitarian aid project co-
ordinator Januario Dotolo.
</P>
<P>
Dotolo said that the second phase of the assistance will focus
on providing seeds, working tools and ensuring food security.
</P>
<P>
The assistance project started in March, 2000, establishing 37
kitchens and a few camping centers for the displaced persons in
the northeastern Balombo district in Benguela province.
</P>
<P>
According to local analysts, the suspension of the aid flights
to the region was mainly due to the rampant guerrilla actions
launched by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Balombo district is neighboring the war-torn Huambo
province, where there have been the most fierce battles between
the Angolan government troops and the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
</TEXT>
