<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen A-Share Market Weekly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen Composite Index
increased 9.09 points or 1.5 percent to end the week at 612.99
points on Friday, while the sub-index edged up 9.75 points or 0.2
percent to 4710.8 points.
</P>
<P>
The turnover this week stood at 37.96 billion yuan, 15.29
percent less than last week's 44.81 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Continuing last week's rebound, the market went in its upward
trend early this week, according to Homeway, China's leading
financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, cheered by the news that Sinopec began to have a
global issue, and that the oil price continued to rise, big-cap
blue chips and petroleum-chem shares performed actively, leading
up the index to the high level of 617.92 points.
</P>
<P>
As the heavy selling pressure was near the 620-point level, the
market failed to touch the target this week. News of the second
board market and the listing of state-owned shares also affected
the market.
</P>
<P>
To set up the second board market as quickly as possible is one
of the important measures for China's stock market reform. With
more news coming about the establishment of China's second board
stock market, investors were more and more concerned about issues
on the new market, including the market name, timing, place, scale,
differentiation, funds flow, liquidity, listing rules, risks and
market future, etc.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the Shenzhen Stock Exchange, the
confirmed news is that the second board market will debut on the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange, and about fifty enterprises are expected
to be firstly listed among 300 applicants.
</P>
<P>
The officials also said the government formally approved the
merger of the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges last month and
the second board market has been proposed to be set up by early
2001.
</P>
<P>
Before the decision on the second board market is clear, the
market will not have a clear direction. Taking a wait-and-see
attitude is what investors can do at present, according to Homeway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen B-Share Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen B-share Index
closed the week flat at 119.12 points. Trading was suspended on
Wednesday due to a public holiday in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
For most of the week, buyers and sellers were in a tug war,
with most people on the sidelines with caution. Trading was in a
mixed fashion, and market breadth had taken on a negative slant,
according to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
Not much lay behind the lackluster except for technical reasons.
The market never tried to get a lift from a friendly batch of
economic news that should have strengthened the belief of a robust
economy in China.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts predict that fairly narrow-range trading will
continue to dominate the sessions ahead and any of the advance may
be hampered with no leaderships as investors are offered no
further encouragement in a buying mood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
