<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-Share Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market
pared gains this week in shrinking trade volume and with much
negativity.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai B-share index dipped 1.47 points or 2.10 percent
to 68.50 at the end of the week, and the five-day turnover
contracted to 69.94 million U.S. dollars, which was 33.26 percent
less than the total of last week.
</P>
<P>
After opening on a strong note, the market failed to sustain
gains and gradually lost ground in four consecutive sessions of
decline. For most of the week, buyers and sellers were in a tug
war, with most people on the sidelines with caution, according to
Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and securities advisory
company.
</P>
<P>
Not much lay behind the lackluster except for technical reasons.
The market turned deaf to a friendly batch of economic news that
has strengthened the belief of a robust economy in China.
</P>
<P>
Homeway analysts predict that the market is likely to be
confined to fairly narrow ranges in the sessions ahead and any of
its advances may be hampered with no leaderships as investors are
offered no further encouragement in a buying mood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
