<HEADLINE> China's T-Bond Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese treasuries were on
track to rally after the slump of last week. Four of the six
outstanding T-bonds saw a tame rise of 0.17 yuan with the other
two unchanged for the week.
</P>
<P>
A bond listed in 1999, 009905, led the rise by picking up 0.26
yuan to 100.25 yuan, and had a 0.04 percentage point loss in the
yield to 3.28 percent, according to Homeway, China's leading on-
line financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
The other gainers were 000696, 000896 and 009908, with advances
ranging from 0.11 percent to 0.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance announced Monday to sell this year's
third issue of certificate bonds worth of 80 billion yuan on
Friday. The issuance includes 48 billion yuan of three-year bonds
with an annual interest rate of 2.89 percent and 32 billion yuan
of five-year bonds with an interest rate of 3.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the first two issues of certificate treasuries met strong
demand, market insiders said that the same case might occur to
this issue.
</P>
<P>
To date, the ministry has issued treasuries valued at 392
billion yuan, including 190 billion yuan of certificates and 102
billion yuan of book-entries, accounting for 68 percent of the
full-year budget for treasury issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
