<HEADLINE> Western-China Photo Show Begins in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Western-China photo show
entitled "West China, Land of Hope" kicked off here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This exhibition will provide the Nepalese people an
opportunity to be enlightened on the western region of China and
its land, people, culture and development," said Tarini Datta
Chatauta, Minister of Culture, Tourism and Civil Aviation, at the
inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely believe that Nepal has a lot to learn from the
success stories of China's policy and far-sighted campaign of
national development," he said. "Let us continue to work towards
further strengthening the ties between Nepal and China and carry
out developmental works for the mutual benefit of both countries."
</P>
<P>
Also speaking on the occasion, Zeng Xuyong, Chinese Ambassador
to Nepal, said that "to accelerate the development of the central
and western region of China is a great strategic decision made by
the Chinese government facing the new century."
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said that this exhibition is aimed at letting
Nepalese people understand China's policy to develop the western
region and attract more foreign investors to participate in China'
s western region's development.
</P>
<P>
China's western region consists of 12 administrative regions,
including six provinces -- Shaanxi, Gansu, Qinghai, Yunnan,
Guizhou and Sichuan, five autonomous regions -- the Inner Mongolia,
the Ningxia Hui, the Xinjiang Uygur, the Tibet and the Guangxi
Zhuang, and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
On display are over 50 photos reflecting the lives of people
and the development of China's western region.
</P>
<P>
About 200 people, including Nepalese officials and people from
all walks of life as well as Chinese diplomats, were present on
the first day of the one-week show co-organized by the Chinese
Embassy and the Arnilo Society, a society of China trained
scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
