<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Has a Crucial Role in Protecting Ozone Layer: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Asian countries have to play
their part in protecting the ozone layer, the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the eve of this year's International Day for the
Preservation of the Ozone Layer Saturday, UNEP Executive Director
Klaus Toepfer said in a press release that attention has to shift
from the industrialized countries, which have led the way in
lowering chlorofluorocarbons (CFC) output, to the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
He urged the developing countries to phase out CFC emissions by
2010, the deadline agreed under the Montreal Protocol.
</P>
<P>
UNEP recently released an update report on which developing
countries will reach their commitments to reduce and phase out
consumption and production of ozone-depleting substances under the
1997 Montreal Protocol.
</P>
<P>
"The trend of compliance is favorable, but we cannot be
complacent. Stakes are very high and together we have to ensure
the continued success of the Protocol," Toepfer said.
</P>
<P>
As part of awareness raising activities throughout the world, a
new code of practice to guide the handling of ozone-depleting
substances used in refrigeration and air conditioning in Thailand
was launched Friday.
</P>
<P>
Toepfer said a significant problem in developing countries was
the release of refrigerants into the atmosphere during maintenance
and servicing of older equipment.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the Parties to the Montreal Protocol on
Substances that Deplete the Ozone Layer met in China and adopted
critical decisions ensuring further
financial support to help developing countries phase out CFCs and
other ozone- depleting substances.
</P>
<P>
However, earlier this month satellites confirmed the current
ozone "hole" over the Antarctic is the largest ever recorded. The
hole measures a record 28.3 million square kilometers, over one
million square kilometers larger than the previous record in 1998.
</P>
<P>
While the ozone layer continues to weaken as the emissions of
past decades gradually drift up to the stratosphere, it is
expected to start recovering in the coming years as more and more
countries adopt ozone-friendly technologies.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent meeting of the UNEP Environmental Effects
Assessment Panel of the Montreal Protocol emphasized that the
timing for this recovery remains uncertain. In particular, the
Panel noted that the interactions between global warming effects
and ozone depletion could delay ozone recovery by an additional
decade.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's International Day for the
Preservation of the Ozone Layer is "Save Our Sky: Protect Yourself;
Protect the Ozone Layer". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Military Kills Over 20 Chechen Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Russian military said
Friday that its artillery Thursday killed over 20 rebels and
injured scores of others in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
These militants were eliminated while Russian federal troops
shelled five rebel concentrations in the Vedeno and Nozhai-Yurt
districts of Chechnya, the Interfax news agency quoted the Russian
armed forces' command in the North Caucasus as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russian sappers disposed two bombing devices near checkpoints
in the Vedeno district, one under the railroad bed in the
Naurskaya district and the other in the railway station of
Gudermes, Chechnya's second biggest city.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 24 hours, rebels fired at federal positions 12
times. Federal units detained 47 suspects and seized 18 automatic
weapons, the command said.
</P>
<P>
In the Chechen capital of Grozny, Russian sappers found and
removed four bombing devices planted on the shoulders of roads,
the command press center said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Russian units also destroyed three rebel bunkers, a truck and
three illicit miniature oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian air force Su-24 bombers flew seven combat
missions and Mi-24 armed helicopters flew over 20 sorties to carry
out air strikes on three rebel camps in the Chechen mountains, the
press center said.
</P>
<P>
Mi-24 helicopters fired missiles at a rebel group that was
poised to attack a Russian military convoy, killing some of the
rebels and scattering the others, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
