<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Spread Trade Ideas to L. America via Live Broadcast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (
WTO) has launched a cycle of videoconferences broadcast live by
satellite from Geneva to university centers in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Each videoconference features a WTO expert who will speak on
trade subjects such as trade in services and dispute settlement,
followed by a question-and-answer session, according to a WTO
press release Friday.
</P>
<P>
WTO Director-General Mike Moore said that the project
highlights "our efforts to reach out to the public using every
accessible modern technology, including the Internet." He said the
organization is already keeping trade communities, especially in
least developed countries, up-to-date on WTO activities through
its Website and electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
In collaboration with Mexico's Monterrey Institute of
Technology and Higher Studies, the WTO videoconference cycle uses
the institute's Virtual University Network, which has local
centers in leading academic institutions in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
WTO Deputy Director-General Miguel Rodriguez opened the
videoconference cycle on August 30, 2000. This inaugural broadcast,
on "Basic Principles and General Overview of the WTO", was
followed by more than 500 students, businessmen and trade
officials in Mexico alone. It was also broadcast to other Latin
American countries.
</P>
<P>
The next WTO videoconference will be held on September 20 with
focus on trade in goods, including the WTO agreements on
agriculture and on textiles. Other WTO subjects to be featured
through November 22 are dispute settlement, trade in services,
trade and environment and trade-related aspects of intellectual
property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
