<HEADLINE> Cuban Boxers Hope for Clean Sweep in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Cuba, a boxing powerhouse, has
sent 12 boxers for all the categories and hoped for a clean sweep
of all the titles in the Syndey Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident of winning the titles because we have the
strongest competitors in almost every category," said Olympic
champion Maikro Romero and World Cup winner Jorge Gutierrez in an
interview with Xinhua on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It's not because we're overplaying our potentials because our
athletes all have great experiences in the world," said Romero.
</P>
<P>
Included in the Cuban boxing contigent are consecutive Olympic
champion Felix Savon in the 91-kg class, 60kg Mario Kindelan, 51-
kg budding star Julio Montilla, 71-kg veteran Juan Hernandez
Sierra and 57kg Enrique Carrion.
</P>
<P>
Since 1968 when Cuba reapt its first boxing medal in the
Mexican City Olympics, Cuban boxers have bagged home a total of 41
Olympic medals including 23 golds 13 silvers and 5 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
The pile of medals were accumulated by Cuban athletes who did
not show up for the 1984 and 1988 Olympics, which composed half of
the total gold medals won by every Cuban Olympic delegations.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, the Cuban boxers had their feat
with seven golds and two silvers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
