<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Friday, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN -- Shenzhen expects to build closer cooperative ties
with Hong Kong and Macao in a wider range of fields in the new
century, said Mayor Yu Youjun.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, which faces Shenzhen of south China's Guangdong
province across a river, has been Shenzhen's leading source of
investment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Shenzhen has approved 21,303 Hong Kong-
financed projects since it became a special economic zone on
August 26, 1980. A total of 13.714 billion U.S. dollars of capital
from Hong Kong had poured into Shenzhen through these projects.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LHASA -- Legqog, chairman of the Tibetan Autonomous Region,
Thursday refuted comments by Western media that the Chinese
government has changed the Tibetans' traditional way of life.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with journalists from both the Chinese mainland
and Taiwan, he said everything the government has done is for the
Tibetans to live a happy life, just like people in other parts of
China.
</P>
<P>
Traditional Tibetan festivals, such as the Tibetan New Year and
the Xodoin Festival are being celebrated as before and with
additional elements of modern lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Chinese government decided that 15 provinces and
municipalities will form a partnership with seven prefectures of
Tibet to promote the development of autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Since then, aid by these regions has greatly helped the
development of infrastructure, culture, education, health and
agriculture in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
DALIAN -- A 5.4 kilometer-long light railway line went into
trial operation Thursday in Dalian City, northeast China's
Liaoning Province. The line is the first light railway line in
China.
</P>
<P>
The train, with a designed speed of 70 kilometers per hour, will
go through the downtown areas in Dalian and is expected to
alleviate the city's traffic jams during rush hours.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI -- The Shanghai Super-computer Center Thursday kicked
off its first application projects, with the signing of co-
operation pacts with several leading research bodies in the city.
</P>
<P>
Among its first customers are the Shanghai Institute of Life
Sciences, the Shanghai Observatory, the Shanghai Pharmaceutical
Research Institute and the Chemistry Department of Fudan
University.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Super Computer Center is a key project under the
Shanghai Information Port Program. Its "Shenwei I" parallel
computer is said to be the 48th fastest commercial computer in the
world.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The growth rate of China's investment in fixed
assets increased 12.7 percent in January-August than in the same
1999 period, reaching 1,195.5 billion yuan (144 billion U.S.
dollars),official statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Export-Import Bank of Korea Thursday said it will
lend 20 million U.S. dollars to Mongolia to improve the country's
communication networks.
</P>
<P>
The contract will help step up economic and diplomatic
cooperation between the two countries and boost South Korean
communication product exports such as cables, a bank spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean bank loaned Mongolia 52 million U.S. dollars
in 1993 and 8 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The deposits at foreign banks operating in South Korea
soared to 7.94 trillion won (some 7.16 billion U.S. dollars) in
the first six months of the year, an increase of 24.7 percent
compared to the end of 1999, the Financial Supervisory Service
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citibank of the United States, which has 11 branches in South
Korea, enjoyed the largest share with 4.9 trillion won (4.45
billion dollars), or 61.7 percent of the total deposits.
</P>
<P>
Despite their increased deposits and savings, foreign banks'
total lending to local clients at the end of June this year
amounted to 9.54 trillion won.
</P>
<P>
Now, 64 bank branches from 44 countries are operating in South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Microsoft Chief Bill Gates Thursday said the
company would invest over 50 million U.S. dollars in the next
three years to make development activities in India a central part
of Microsoft's global operations.
</P>
<P>
The company's India development center, he said, would work on
a strategic technology area of the .net platform and build key
product for the same.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to expand its market in India, Microsoft would
also work on local language enabled software over the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Gates discussed possibilities of increasing
the use of information technology in governance and education at
an interactive session with chief ministers of 10 states in the
country.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The value of air trade between the United States and
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)has seen an
average annual growth rate of 14 percent during the last decade,
according to a report issued by the U.S.-ASEAN Business Council
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the 1990-1999 period, the value of U.S.-
ASEAN trade by air route increased from 20.3 billion U.S. dollars
to 67.6 billion dollars, equal to 6.5 percent of the gross
domestic product of the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Two-way air trade also has created 350,000 jobs in the region,
it said.
</P>
<P>
