</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Thai baht slipped to a 25-month low against the
U.S. dollar Thursday and appeared set to reach the 42-baht level,
but Bank of Thailand (BOT) sees no need at the moment to intervene
in the market to prop up the currency, The Nation newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The baht's weakness raised concern that the continuing currency
slide could break the central bank's 3.5-percent inflation target,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Chatu Mongol Sonakul, the BOT governor, was quoted as saying
the baht is simply tracking regional currency weakness and his
bank won't intervene at this point.
</P>
<P>
However, he didn't say when the central bank would intervene.
</P>
