<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes New Measures to Boost Rice Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese government decided
to dismantle the country's system of export quotas as well as the
practice of licensing exports through state appointed firms in
order to boost rice export, Vietnam News (VNS) reported here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision is expected to go into effect as of early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the country's new government policies
encouraging rice export have contributed greatly to the
development of the domestic rice market.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, Vietnamese Ministry of Trade will
coordinate with other ministries and agencies to draw up a new
mechanism governing market control and stabilization.
</P>
<P>
The new document will lay out measures aiming at ensuring
stable rice supplies, food security, and an end to unorganized
rice trade.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam expects that 500,000 tons of rice will be exported this
month, bringing the total export since the beginning of the year
to between 2.8 and 2.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's rice export plan this year remains unchanged though
rice cultivation has been badly hit by floods and storms.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Vietnam officially joined the international rice
market, and since then its export volume has increased
considerably thanks to the constant improvement of rice quality.
</P>
<P>
Rice export increased from 1.4 million tons in 1989 to 4.5
million tons last year. As a result, Vietnamese rice accounted for
20 percent of the world market as of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
