<HEADLINE> Manila Hopeful of U.S. Military Aid Amid Cohen's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Friday it is hopeful that the visit of the U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen would give a much-needed impetus to the
modernization efforts of the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio interview
that President Joseph Estrada would discuss the matter with
Secretary Cohen, who is scheduled to pay him a courtesy call in
the presidential palace Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Cohen received a warm welcome by his Philippine counterpart
Orlando Mercado following the former's arrival in Manila Friday
afternoon. After a short welcome ceremony, Cohen and Mercado went
directly for a close-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are examining our foreign military assistance. We are
looking into the military's requirements, particularly that of our
Army and Navy," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the president would follow up with Cohen the
promise of U.S. officials to help the Philippines in its military
modernization program.
</P>
<P>
During Estrada's working visit to the United States in July, he
received a commitment from U.S. President Bill Clinton to help the
Philippines modernize its military forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government stressed the immediate needs of the
Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP), particularly boats for
patrol and helicopters for search-and-rescue operations. 
</P>
