<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Majority Backs PM's Civic Reforms: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Israelis
support the sweeping civic reforms proposed by Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, according to a survey conducted on behalf of the Israeli
leading daily The Jerusalem Post published on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reform proposals polled by the Smith Institute, a long-
established polling company in Israel, included allowing stores in
city centers to remain open, public transportation to operate, and
state-run airline El Al to fly on Shabbat, and permitting civil
marriages.
</P>
<P>
The most popular move is removing the ban imposed on El Al,
which is intended to facilitate the airline's privatization. Sixty-
four percent of the 502 respondents are in favor, which 34 percent
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
Even among those who consider themselves "traditional", there
was backing for Shabbat flights from 51 percent of those
questioned.
</P>
<P>
The most controversial issue was that of opening shops in malls
and commercial centers, with 53 percent saying it would be a good
idea and 45 percent objecting.
</P>
<P>
On civil marriage, the margin of support was of 56 percent to 41
percent, and on public transportation on Shabbat, which was
intended by the prime minister to provide bus services particularly
for the careless immigrants in Tel Aviv area, the approval rating
was nearly as high as on El Al, with 60 percent approving and 38
percent opposing.
</P>
<P>
Among secular respondents, 91 percent said El Al should fly on
Shabbat. Support for all the proposals was overwhelming, with the
lowest level of support coming for opening shops, with 77 percent
in favor and 21 percent against.
</P>
<P>
Among those classified as "religious and haredi (ultra-
Orthodox)", opposition to all the suggestions was far greater than
the backing expressed by secular participants. Concerning both
public transportation and allowing stores to open, 94 percent said
they are opposed. On civil marriage and El Al, 92 percent objected.
</P>
<P>
The survey, with a 4.5-percent margin of error, represents a
cross-section of Jewish adults in Israel, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The poll followed Barak's announcement that he intends to
promote a "socio-civil" reform plan aimed at modernizing the
Israeli society. The issues questioned in the poll constitute the
bulk of the plan.
</P>
<P>
In response to the findings, the Prime Minister's Office said it
is "sure that the prime minister's proposals reflect the needs and
genuine interests of the large majority of Israelis, religious and
secular alike."
</P>
<P>
The poll also drew criticism from the religious factions of the
society. Knesset (Parliament) Member Avraham Ravitz from the United
Torah Judaism Party was quoted as saying that the respondents
included "a lot of confused people", who are not sure what to make
of the religious-secular dispute.
</P>
<P>
He charged that those leading the reforms are guilty of "
stealing away" the Jewish identity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Barak met Ashkenazi Chief Rabbi Yisael Meir Lau at his Defense
Ministry office in Tel Aviv and told Lau that "the actions in
advancing and carrying out the components of the civil-social
agenda shall be done through dialogue, attention, and maximum
understanding of all streams among the public, but without damaging
the authority of the executive branch to conduct the affairs of the
state in a manner which serves the needs of its citizens, and
without giving any sector the right to veto decisions of the
elected government."
</P>
<P>
The principles of Barak's social-civic reforms have been
approved by the ruling Labor Party's senior echelon without any
objections, though some members of the executive committee
expressed opposition.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, though left with a shaky minority
government, said he believes that he has coalition partners for
both the peace process with the Palestinians and for the civic
reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
