reforms implemented, according to a survey conducted on behalf of
the Jerusalem Post by the Smith Institute. The polls surveyed 502
people on Sunday and Monday, representing a cross-section of Jewish
adults in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The reforms polled included allowing stores in city centers to
remain open, public transportation to operate, and Israel's El Al
airline to fly on Shabbat, and permitting civil marriage.
</P>
<P>
The most popular move, according to the poll, is lifting the ban
imposed on EL Al. Among the general public, 64 percent are in
favor, while 34 percent oppose it.
</P>
