<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Build World's Second Largest Nature Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will incorporate fossil
beds found in a village of southwestern province Mugla in 1993 into
a nature park nearby to establish the second largest outdoor nature
museum in the world, Turkish Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project, under the auspices of the Culture Ministry and the
Mugla Governorship, will be named the Turolian Nature Park 2000.
The nature park will be the world's second largest one with the
first in the U.S. state of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, a local inhabitant in the Ozluce village close to the
Aegean Sea discovered fossils of animals that lived 5-10 million
years ago. Since then, excavations started and will continue until
the middle of November of this year.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said that the fossils belong to the forerunners
of modern-day cattle, giraffes, rhinoceros, large-snouted animals,
pigs and horses.
</P>
<P>
They urged the government to take emergent measures to protect
the fossil beds containing the remains of many prehistoric
animals. "The fossils are being collected and sold by locals. We
intend to introduce and promote the region's natural and cultural
wealth to the world by the park project," they said.
</P>
<P>
Mugla Governor Lutfi Yigenoglu said that the city of Mugla and
its environs, neighboring the Aegean Sea, were suited to becoming
an outdoor museum.
</P>
<P>
In order to have an outdoor nature museum established at the
Ozluce fossil beds, they needed funds to conduct preliminary
surveys, and carry out construction and renovation activities, the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
He said that they would work in collaboration with Greece to
secure the funds from the European Union's environment and culture
fund. 
