<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia on Singapore Senior Minister's Memoirs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Friday
Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew's second volume of memoirs
should not strain the good ties between Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's policy towards Singapore remains one of fostering
the spirit of neighborliness based on mutual respect and
understanding for the benefit of both countries, the Foreign
Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It should be regarded as a portrayal of history as viewed by
Lee, and not the official viewpoint of the Singapore government,
it said.
</P>
<P>
"As the memoirs are the interpretations and personal views of
Lee Kuan Yew and might have formed the basis of the Singapore
government's policy sometime in the past, it cannot be considered
the Singapore government's official stand now on bilateral ties
between the two countries," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The memoirs, among other things, touched on the history of
relations between Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Extracts of the memoirs were published in the Singapore Straits
Times newspaper last week.
</P>
<P>
Lee served as Singapore's first prime minister for 31 years
until 1990.
</P>
<P>
Lee will launch the second volume of his memoirs entitled "From
Third World to First" on his 77th birthday in Singapore Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
