<HEADLINE> Southern African Farmers Not Ready for Free Trade Area: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Southern African
Countries are not ready for the Free Trade Area because the sector
is characterized by so many weak elements, visiting president of
the International Federation of Agricultural Producers (IFAP)
Gerald Doornbos has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambian newspaper the Post Friday quoted Doornbos as saying
that most developing countries have a lot of problems in the
agricultural commodity production costs and are not ready for the
FTA, which will be launched by the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) next month, because they are still
undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
"Governments in developing countries must be aware of the low
prices of agricultural commodities and look at ways of
strengthening the sector," the president said, adding "farmers
cannot enter the FTA if their base is not developed."
</P>
<P>
He also called for unity among farmers in the country in order
to develop a strong market position as they enter an integrated
market. 
</P>
