<HEADLINE> Chinese Treasuries Up on Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The overall Chinese T-bond
market were buoyant helped by a minor capital inflow from the
equity market, when domestic stocks kept reeling amid market
speculations about the establishment of the second board.
</P>
<P>
The transaction value totaled 1.79 billion yuan, up 423 million
yuan from yesterday, according to Homeway, China's leading
financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
The ten-year floating rate 010004, whose interest rate stays at
2.87 percent this year, rebounded after the two-day slip. The bond
jumped by 0.42 percent to lead the rise, pressing the yield down 0.
04 percentage points to 2.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
000896 (8.56 percent, due 2003) followed the advance by picking
up 0.16 percent to 123.45 yuan, accompanied by a 0.05 percentage
point drop in its yield, which closed at 3.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
009704 (9.78 percent, due 2007) saw a tame rise of 0.03 percent
to close at 134.82 yuan, while the rest, 000696 (11.83 percent,
due 2006), 009905 (3.28 percent, due 2007) and 0009908 (3.30
percent, due 2009), lingered around present levels.
</P>
<P>
China's repurchasing transaction expanded fueled by IPOs.
Combined trade volume of three-day, seven-day, 14-day, and 28-day
repurchasing transactions increased 3.26 billion yuan further to 9.
99 billion yuan. However, the interest rate of the three-day
repurchasing agreement plunged from 3.3 percent to 1.28 percent.
</P>
