<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Party Moves Motion to Condemn Police Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition Movement
for Democratic Change (MDC) Thursday moved a motion in Parliament
to condemn the raid of its offices by police, the Herald reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moving the motion, MDC Secretary General Welshman Ncube said
the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-
pf) was using unlawful means to undermine his party ahead of
presidential elections in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Ncube told Parliament that the raid was "an attempt by Zanu-pf
to access MDC documents containing information about the party and
strategies for the forthcoming presidential elections".
</P>
<P>
Police searched for weapons in the MDC offices in Harare on
Thursday, but failed to find such things.
</P>
<P>
He urged the House to condemn the "harassment" by police and
called on the police not to act as an agent of Zanu-pf, but to be
political and professional in the discharge of their duties.
</P>
<P>
However, leader of the House Patrick Chinamasa, who is from the
Zanu-pf, said he noted the serious concerns of the MDC lawmakers,
but said it was unfortunate that they were not able to distinguish
between Zanu-pf and police.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Zanu-pf is not the police and the police are not Zanu-
pf."
</P>
<P>
Parliament could not give a judgment on an issue that had not
yet been concluded, said Chinamasa.
</P>
<P>
MDC Leader in Parliament Gibson Sibanda urged Minister of Home
Affair John Nkomo to restore the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo said he would look into the matter and issue a statement
to Parliament on Tuesday next week.
</P>
<P>
The MDC Thursday also lodged an urgent application in the High
Court to prevent the police from further searching the party's
offices for arms of war. The court application was expected to be
heard Friday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
