<HEADLINE> Insecurity Rising in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
admitted that there is a serious upsurge of insecurity in the east
African country, the major newspaper East African Standard
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted State Minister Marsden Madoka as saying the
country is experiencing an increase of violent crime like cattle
rustling, banditry, political crimes and ethnic tension.
</P>
<P>
Madoka said on Thursday that deteriorated insecurity is
hampering economic development and he attributed the rising
insecurity to illegal arms from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"National security is at stake because of illegal aliens who
have crossed the borders secretly and the proliferation of
firearms is exacerbated by the conflicts in neighboring countries,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of these illegal aliens have been found to engage in
criminal activities such as arms dealings, drug trafficking,
social and economic crimes," said Madoka.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is implementing strategies geared
towards equipping the police so that they can overcome challenges
of insecurity.
</P>
<P>
The government has also committed to improving the welfare of
officers by addressing their remuneration, housing and transport
facilities, according to Madoka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
