<HEADLINE> Zambian Farmers Urge Govt. to Secure Fertilizer Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia National Farmers Union
(ZNFU) has urged the government to take measures to secure
fertilizer supply or the farmers may face a critical shortage of
urea in the coming agriculture season two months away, Times of
Zambia reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU President Ajay Vashee was quoted as saying here on
Thursday that there are indications that there would be a serious
shortage of urea on the world market and last minute contingencies
would only serve to hurt Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said that ZNFU is concerned about the preparations for the
2000-2001 farming season.
</P>
<P>
Vashee noted the country's fertilizer requirement stands
between 100,000 tons and 120,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
He said in Ndola, the capital city of Copperbelt province, that
his organization has urged the government to remove value added
tax (VAT) on all inputs for small farmers because the farmers have
no capacity to reclaim the VAT.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Agriculture Minister Yotam Ngulube said that the
government is ready to help in the development of the small scale
farming sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
