<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Attorney-General Denies Corrupt Country Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Attorney General Amos
Wako has protested against the ranking of Kenyan among the ten
most corrupt countries in the world by the Transparency
International.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the Germany-based organization's rating, which
placed Kenya 82nd out of 90 countries, Wako claimed the ranking
was unfair.
</P>
<P>
"We hear and know what is happening in a number of countries,"
he said. "I know what is happening in Kenya and the ranking cannot
be correct."
</P>
<P>
Wako said that the rating failed to acknowledge Kenya's anti-
graft measures in the past year.
</P>
<P>
He defended Kenya's record by citing the publication of the
Anti-corruption and Economic Crimes Bill and a code of conduct for
public servants.
</P>
<P>
The report, released on Tuesday by the organization, ranked
Nigeria as the most corrupt nation in the world, and acknowledged
the anti-graft measures can not bring about results overnight.
</P>
<P>
However Wako credited the organization with having done a good
job by sensitizing the international community to corruption.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the ranking, the government is committed to a zero
tolerance policy towards corruption," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
