<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will visit Vietnam in
November, the first of its kind since the end of the Vietnam War
25 years ago, the White House said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart said the trip, which will
take place after Clinton attends the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) forum in mid-November in Brunei, would both be
substantive and symbolic. (Vietnam-Clinton-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine government negotiators are hopeful that
two French journalists being held hostage by Abu Sayyaf rebels in
the southern Philippines will be freed in the next 24 hours, a TV
report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Jacques Le Garrec and Roland Madura of the France-2
Television Channel should have been freed last week if not for a
squabble over money between two Abu Sayyaf factions, the ABS-CBN
TV network said. (Philippines-Hostages)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate on Thursday rejected the last six
proposed amendments to a bill on permanent normal trade relations
(PNTR) with China, and is scheduled to vote on the legislation
next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Since it began debates on the legislation on September 5, the
Senate have defeated a total of 19 amendments trying to link the
PNTR bill with human rights, prison labor, abortion, weapons
proliferation and other issues. One of the six amendments defeated
on Thursday was a measure proposed by Senator Ernest Hollings on
trade deficits with China. (US Senate-China-PNTR)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Senior Indonesian officials held closed-door
meetings in Bali with East Timor leader Xanana Gusmao and U.N.
officials late on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first encounter between Indonesian government
officials on the one hand and East Timorese leaders and U.N.
officials on the other since an attack left three U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR) workers dead in Atambua,
Indonesia, last week. (Indonesia-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The European Central Bank (ECB) announced Thursday
that it would buy 2.5 billion euros with the interest income from
foreign currency reserves, but didn't mention whether the move is
designed to support the sagging euro.
</P>
<P>
But ECB Chairman Wim Duisenberg was quoted by the German press,
saying "if you want, you can describe the measure as intervention.
" According to an ECB statement, at the beginning of 1999, the
bank was provided with foreign reserve assets with a then-market
value of about 39.5 billion euros. (ECB-Euros-Buy) 
</P>
