<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Drops Ahead of Rate Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso was
slightly weaker against the U.S. dollar early Friday ahead of the
country's central bank's possible further intervention.
</P>
<P>
The peso averaged 45.615, weaker compared to the previous close
of 45.605.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said banks stayed at the sidelines, keeping a watchful
eye for another rate hike announcement.
</P>
<P>
"Banks are on guard and are not too enthusiastic for the dollar
pending the rate hike announcement," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The policy-making Monetary Board meets Friday to decide whether
it will raise overnight rates again to further ease pressure on
the peso which dived to a new 32-month intra-day low of 45.950
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank raised its overnight borrowing rate to 11%
from 10% and its overnight lending rate to 13.25% from 12.25%
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the peso is seen trading within a tight 45.6 to 45.
8 range against the dollar for the rest of Friday's session, but
may have a chance to test the 45.5 support level in case the
central bank raises its overnight rates again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
