<HEADLINE> New Zealand Opposition Party Gains in Support: Poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Support for the major
ruling party, the Labor Party, has slumped, with its main rival,
the National Party, surging ahead for the first time since the
November election, according to a local poll published Friday.
</P>
<P>
The National Business Review-Compaq poll of 750 people puts
support for the major opposition party, the National Party, at 41
percent, ahead of the Labor Party on 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party's support is well down from a post-election
high of 48 percent recorded by the same poll in March 1999, at
which time the then ruling party, the National Party, was polling
at its lowest ever level, 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Observers here attribute the falling support for the Labor
Party mainly to the drops of the country's business confidence and
the New Zealand dollar to record lows. 
</P>
