<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Weakens Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- High demand for U.S. dollars
in the energy sector, coupled with low supply of the currency, has
further weakened Kenyan shilling this week.
</P>
<P>
The shilling weakened to an average of 78.08 shillings to the
dollar on Thursday from 72 shillings in early August, the major
newspaper Daily Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers said that the Kenya Power and Lighting Company
placed an order for 6 million dollars last week to import fuels
and generators, which was suspected to have weakened the shilling
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the shilling could still remain weak for
some time if demand persists, adding that proceeds from tea
exports were slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Kanga, the chief economist with the Central Bank of
Kenya, said he was sure an inflation target of five percent by the
end of the financial year in June 2001 would be met despite upward
pressure from a weak shilling, drought and higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
An acute drought which has caused severe food shortages, water
and electricity rationing had led some economists to conclude that
Kenya would miss its inflation target.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's inflation dropped from a peak of 46 percent in 1993 to
3.5 percent last year. Inflation in the first half of this year
rose to 6.7 percent, partly due to drought, but figures for July
and August showed a dip to 5.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
