<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Not to Intervene as Baht Hits 25-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai baht slipped to a 25-
month low against the U.S. dollar Thursday and appeared set to
reach the 42-baht level, but Bank of Thailand (BOT) sees no need
at the moment to intervene in the market to prop up the currency,
The Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The baht's weakness raised concern that the continuing currency
slide could break the central bank's 3.5-percent inflation target,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the baht weakness to sustained dollar demand,
both offshore and domestic, triggered by political uncertainty and
unfavorable sentiment toward regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
Chatu Mongol Sonakul, the BOT governor, was quoted as saying
the baht is simply tracking regional currency weakness and his
bank won't intervene at this point.
</P>
<P>
However, he didn't say when the central bank would intervene.
</P>
<P>
The baht Thursday briefly dove to 41.86 against the greenback
in early trade before bouncing back to 41.7 in the afternoon
session.
</P>
<P>
A senior dealer at a Thai bank said that if the baht continued
to fall it would have some impact on the central bank's inflation
target.
</P>
<P>
It is widely anticipated that if the baht fell to 42 against
the greenback it would effectively force the BOT to jack up short-
term interest rates in a bid to tame inflation.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said he was
concerned about the falling baht and would raise the issue with
the central bank at the economic ministers' meeting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Although the government would like to maintain its non-
interference policy at the central bank, the weak baht and low
interest rates worry us and we have to talk with the central bank
about these issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the baht was partly undermined by bearish
sentiment on regional currencies sparked by Wednesday's bombing of
the Jakarta stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Many have said the baht is poised to fall further as the BOT
signaled that it would counter the weakened baht with a low
interest-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
The signal is evident in the central bank's recent request that
commercial banks lower their lending rates to help bolster the
persistently sluggish economy. Many banks have trimmed both
deposit and lending rates by 25 basis points.
</P>
<P>
The baht has also been affected by political uncertainty ahead
of the general election, which must be called by November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suicide Bombing Kills 4, Injures 20 in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A suicide bomber of the
separatist Tamil Tiger rebels of Sri Lanka exploded himself here
on Friday morning, killing four people and injuring more than 20
others, police said.
</P>
<P>
The blast took place near the National Hospital in the heart of
Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka. It is still unknown whom the
suicide bomber had been targeted.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence reports have warned that about 20 Tamil Tiger
suicide bombers had infiltrated Colombo to target both government
and opposition politicians who are busy with election campaigns
for the forthcoming general elections scheduled for October 10.
</P>
<P>
A total of 29 political parties and 99 independent groups will
contest the general elections with the ruling People's Alliance
and main opposition United National Party as arch rivals.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the dissolution of the parliament on August 18,
election-related violence is on rapid increase in the country
which is haunted by successive violence especially in the election
campaign. The government has blamed most of the violent incidents
on the Tamil Tiger rebels, whose formidable suicide bombers are
frequent attackers.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga narrowly escaped an
assassination attempt during last December's presidential election
but lost her vision in the right eye. A suicide bomber of Tamil
Tiger rebels carried out the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
