<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Looking Good: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Having already grown by 17
percent year-on-year in the first eight months of this year,
Thailand's exports will exceed this year's target, Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai was quoted Friday by The Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Thai export sector has performed exceptionally well despite
the challenges posed by the crisis, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The country's export during the first seven months grew by 21.3
percent to 39 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Along with the upswing in exports, the government is also
encouraged by the continuing fall in unemployment, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
Businesses with more than 10 workers have been hiring more
people over the last year, according to the social security office.
</P>
<P>
Before the crisis hit Thailand in 1997, about 6.2 million
workers contributed to the social security fund. By early last
year when unemployment was at its peak, the number of workers
contributing to the fund fell to 5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
The employment situation has improved to the point that about 5.
92 million workers now contribute to the fund, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commerce Ministry has recently revised the
country's export target for the whole year to a growth rate of 9.5
to 12 percent, from the previous forecast of a 6-percent growth,
or 56.4 billion dollars in total.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said the revised target should not be difficult to reach.
To achieve it, he said, exporters will have to focus more on
market demand and international standard requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
