<HEADLINE> Officials of Indonesia, East Timor Discuss Refugee Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Senior Indonesian officials
held closed-door meetings in Bali with East Timor leader Xanana
Gusmao and U.N. officials late on Thursday, reports reaching here
Friday said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first encounter between Indonesian government
officials on the one hand and East Timorese leaders and U.N.
officials on the other since an attack left three U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR) workers dead in Atambua,
Indonesia, last week.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Indonesian delegation Coordinating Minister for
Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono
said the meeting was aimed at "finding a comprehensive settlement
to the East Timor refugee issue." But Gusmao hinted that the talks
also touched on cross-border incidents.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the meeting, Indonesian officials also held talks with
pro-Jakarta East Timorese militia leaders in Bali.
</P>
<P>
One of the East Timorese militia leaders, Eurico Guterres, said
after the meeting that the Indonesian government offered East
Timorese refugees a vacant island to live on.
</P>
<P>
"I accept the offer as a token of appreciation form the
government of Indonesia. But I don't know what sort of island it
will be."
</P>
<P>
There are still 130,000 East Timorese refugees in Indonesia's
East Nusa Tenggara Province. They left their homes after last year
's U.N.-sponsored vote during which most people voted for
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
But, in the past few months conflicts between East Timorese
militiamen and U.N. peacekeeping forces have been increasing and
several U.N. soldiers were killed along the border areas.
</P>
<P>
On September 6, the pro-Jakarta militia killed three UNHCR
workers in Atambua,a city in East Nusa Tenggara Province of
Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
