<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Extends State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The state of emergency in Sri
Lanka has been extended till October 4 by voting in the parliament
which was re-summoned Thursday following its dissolution on August
18.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga re-summoned the parliament to
debate on her proclamation of the extension from September 4 to
October 4. Under the constitution, such extension requires
approval of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The parliament voted for the extension by 101 votes in favor
and five against. While the main opposition United National Party
abstained from voting, four Tamil United Liberation Front members
and one member of the Sri Lanka People's Front opposed it.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency needed to be extended because of the
ongoing civil war in the country's north and east, where the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam have been fighting a bloody war
against government troops for 17 years for a separate state for
minority Tamils.
</P>
<P>
Security reports indicated that the Tiger rebels are targeting
leading politicians of both the government and opposition in the
run-up to the elections scheduled for October 10. On earlier
occasions too they had sent suicide bombers to attack southern
politicians and President Kumaratunga was herself such a target
during last December's presidential election. She escaped the
assassination attempt with the loss of her vision in the right eye
and some other minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency allows for special security measures to
be adopted. But under the constitution the election cannot be held
under a state of emergency. With its expiration on October 4, it
may not be extended again till after the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
