<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN-U.S. Air Trade Grows 14 Percent Annually in Last Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The value of air trade
between the United States and the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN)has seen an average annual growth rate of 14
percent during the last decade,according to a report issued by the
U.S.-ASEAN Business Council here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by a visiting delegation of top officials
from the U.S.-based council, said that in the 1990-1999 period,
the value of U.S.-ASEAN trade by air route increased from 20.3
billion U.S. dollars to 67.6 billion dollars, equal to 6.5 percent
of the gross domestic product of the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Two-way air trade also has created 350,000 jobs in the region,
it said.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai earlier
this week, the delegation said that as regional production of high-
technology items increases, the need for air trade services in
ASEAN countries will grow at an estimated 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also urged the ASEAN countries to fully
liberalize the air trade market and adopt an "open-sky" policy to
further boost the trade.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Thailand, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore,
Indonesia, Brunei, Laos, Vietnam, Cambodia and Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
