<HEADLINE> European Central Bank To Buy Euros </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
announced Thursday that it would buy 2.5 billion euros with the
interest income from foreign currency reserves, but didn't mention
whether the move is designed to support the sagging euro.
</P>
<P>
But ECB Chairman Wim Duisenberg was quoted by the German press,
saying "if you want, you can describe the measure as intervention.
"
</P>
<P>
According to an ECB statement, at the beginning of 1999, the
bank was provided with foreign reserve assets with a then-market
value of about 39.5 billion euros.
</P>
<P>
The ECB holdings of foreign currencies have increased by over 2.
5 billion euros after being invested, and the interest income
comprises mostly US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the announcement, the exchange rate of euros
to US dollars increased to 1:0.8738 at the Frankfurt market, but
fell again to 1:0.8680.
</P>
<P>
The euro has been steadily falling in recent months and dropped
to a historic low of 85.64 U.S. cents before the ECB' announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
