<HEADLINE> Athens Olympics Organizers Reject Charges of Overspending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Athens 2004 Olympics
organizers rejected accusations of overspending from politicians
and the media on Thursday and denied that their salaries were too
high.
</P>
<P>
Politicians were outraged when newspapers reported earlier this
week that some organizing committee (ATHOC) staff were earning 10
million drachmas (256,800 U.S. dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think any Greek should be paid this kind of money...
which is four times the prime minister's salary," ruling socialist
party deputy and former sports minister George Lianis said in an
Athens radio station.
</P>
<P>
ATHOC counter-attacked in a statement saying that the
government had yet to decide remuneration for board members and
the salaries of their staff were below-market.
</P>
<P>
"Athens 2004 executives know their responsibilities well," the
statement said. "Greece is called to overcome in the next four
years problems that have tested...great countries."
</P>
<P>
ATHOC has been under tremendous pressure from the International
Olympic Committee (IOC) to speed up long-delayed preparations for
the Games.
</P>
<P>
Delays mainly in venues construction and other areas had forced
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch to give serious warnings to
Athens in April. Impressive progress however had been made ever
since.
</P>
<P>
The salaries row erupted when Culture Minister Theodoros
Pangalos, who has most of the government responsibility for the
Olympics preparations, cancelled plans to join other Greek
officials at the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
The media suggested that the minister was angry with ATHOC for
overspending and over the salaries of some committee members.
Pangalos denied the reports, saying he had too much work in Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
