<HEADLINE> Koreans March under "Unification" Flag for Opening Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- For the first time, DPR Korea
and South Korea will march side by side under a "unification" flag
with a simple name "Korea" at the opening ceremony of the
Millennium Olympic Games here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
They will wear unified uniforms of dark blue jackets and beige
pants with a badge bearing a blue map of the Korean peninsula,
which were made in Seoul and paid by IOC at a cost of US dollars
30,000 dollars, sources said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the Koreas formed unified teams for the World Table
Tennis and Youth Soccer Championships, but never marched together
at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
And it will also be the first time since 1956 when East and
West Germany had their athletes walking side by side in the
Melbourne Olympics.
</P>
<P>
When the opening ceremony in Sydney will miss their national
flags, the Koreas, however, will compete under their own flags and
names in the fortnight games.
</P>
<P>
South Korean are competing in all but five events of canoe,
equestrian, modern pentathlon, softball and triathlon, aiming for
10 to 12 gold medals, while DPR Korean are taking part in fewer
than 10 events, including judo, weightlifting, wrestling, boxing,
gymnastics, shooting and archery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
