<HEADLINE> IOC to Consider Olympic Scale in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) might consider to cut the number of people
involved in Summer Games in the future.
</P>
<P>
IOC said on Friday it would discuss the scale of the games when
Olympic chiefs review the Sydney games after it finishes.
</P>
<P>
IOC director general Francois Carrard said he did not believe
the Games, which open on Friday, were getting too big to handle.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "We will have a postmortem as quickly as possible
after the Sydney Games to see what is really the impact of these
numbers.
</P>
<P>
"The media is 21,000 here. It was around 12,000 in Barcelona (
at the 1992 Games). Everywhere there are increases and we have to
watch that very closely and monitor it. The IOC will sit down and
reconsider where we could possibly put some limits."
</P>
<P>
Triathlon, women's weightlifting and taekwondo will all be
medal events for the first time in Sydney. 
