<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Send Special Envoy to UN for Atambua Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
will soon send a special envoy to the United Nations headquarters
in New York to discuss settlement of the Atambua incident, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy will leave for New York on September 16,
Antara News Agency Friday quoted Cabinet Secretary Marsillam
Simanjontak as saying. But he did not disclose the envoy's name.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report from New York quoted Indonesian Foreign
Minister Alwi Shihab as saying President Abdurrahman Wahid would
assign Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security
Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono to go to New York to talk with
the U.N. Security Council about the settlement of the Atambua
incident.
</P>
<P>
In the incident on September 6, a mob of pro-Jakarta East
Timorese militia attacked and burned the office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees in Atambua, a city in East Nusa Tenggara
Province of Indonesia, killing three of the U.N. agency's relief
workers.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the U.N. Security Council has agreed to
drop its plan to send a special mission to investigate the Atambua
incident and instead assign a team consisting of foreign diplomats
posted in Jakarta to do the job, Marsillam Simanjontak told the
press Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Security Council has agreed it is not necessary to
send a special mission to Atambua as the job can as well be done
by the diplomatic representatives of several countries in Jakarta,
" he said after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government would invite the foreign envoys to go
to Atambua, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Atambua incident ignited strong international criticism and
on September 8, the U.N. Security Council decided to send a
special mission to Indonesia to investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
After East Timor got independence in August last year from
Indonesia, more than 200,000 refugees came to Indonesia to avoid
the violence there.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some 130,000 East Timorese refugees are still living
in camps in parts of East Nusa Tenggara near the border with East
Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
