<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 5 Million Child Laborers in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 5 million children
and teen-agers in Mexico work for 5 to 8 dollars a day, an
official report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A study of the National System for Complete Family Development
(DIF) stated that 64 percent of Mexican children work in farming,
fishing and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, entitled "Prevention, Attention,
Discouragement and Eradication of Childhood Labor," about 28
percent of child laborers work in northern Mexico, where they are
engaged in agricultural work. They work, on average, 9 or 13 hours
a day in the countryside for less than 8 dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
In urban areas, over 10,000 children aged 6 to 14 work on the
streets. About 45 percent of them work in big cities, especially
in Mexico City, the capital of the country, and in tourist sites
and border areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 percent of the children survive by begging, 24 percent
by selling goods, and others by doing subcontracting work.
</P>
<P>
About 8 out of every 10 kids begin working before they are 14
years old, and their average daily income, in cities, is barely
over 5 dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The phenomenon of child labor is linked to poverty, social
inequality and the absence of the possibility to go to school,"
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
