<HEADLINE> Spain Firm in Cracking Down on ETA: King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Spanish King Juan Carlos I,
ending his 4-day visit to Portugal, said Thursday in an address to
the Portuguese Congress that his country must be firm in the fight
against the Basque separatist group ETA.
</P>
<P>
No one should be weak before assassinations and violence and no
one should hesitate in the fight against terrorism, said Juan
Carlos.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said he stands
firmly behind Spain in its fight against terrorism, according to
media reports here.
</P>
<P>
ETA has been held responsible for the deaths of 781 people in
its 32 years of armed struggle for self-determination in northern
Spain and southern France, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Its summer offensive of bombings and assassinations has been
the bloodiest in a decade.
</P>
<P>
ETA's official political wing said Thursday that King Juan
Carlos and Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar "would not be welcome"
in Hernani, a Basque separatist stronghold where they were
expected to visit Saturday with German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Early Wednesday, Spanish police arrested 20 members of EKIN,
ETA's underground leadership unit, in a series of raids across the
country. 
