<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit Vietnam in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton will visit Vietnam in November, the first of its kind
since the end of the Vietnam War 25 years ago, the White House
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart said the trip, which will
take place after Clinton attends the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) summit in mid-November in Brunei, would both be
substantive and symbolic.
</P>
<P>
"The president believes that ... consensus has developed in
this country over the last few years that the time was right to
move forward with this relationship," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton "will address the range of issues we hope to
advance with the people and government of Vietnam following the
normalization of our ties with their country."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman listed several issues Washington hoped to deal
with during Clinton's visit to Vietnam, which is expected to last
a few days.
</P>
<P>
"Trade is one of them; accounting for U.S. servicemen; and we
have a joint cooperative effort on looking at the impact of Agent
Orange," Lockhart said, referring to a defoliant used by the U.S.
forces during the War.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Vietnam have signed a landmark deal this year,
paving the way for normal trade relations between the two
countries. The agreement is yet to be ratified by the U.S.
Congress. 
