<HEADLINE> Chile Gears Up for World Cup Qualifier against Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chile's national soccer team,
coached by Nelson Acosta, is taking every measures for their next
match in the regional qualification for the 2002 World Cup finals
to be hosted by South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
And things are being done to minimize the effect of the high
altitude -- 2,850 meters above sea level -- in Quito, where they
will take on Ecuador October 8, Chilean newspaper "la Segunda"
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador and Chile face off in Olimpico Atahualpa stadium in the
Ecuadorian capital, in a ninth-round South American qualifying
game for the 2002 World Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
Italo Traverso, the physical trainer for the Chilean team, told
the local press that the Chilean squad will arrive five or six
days before the game to get accustomed to the difference in
altitude.
</P>
<P>
Traverso is currently in Quito along with the administrator of
the Chilean Soccer Federation (FCHF), Pablo Hoffman, to set the
schedule for the team's pre-game training.
</P>
<P>
The Chileans had arrived in high-altitude cities on the day of
the game and the sudden change of altitude usually caused problems
to the players. "We had a bad experience in La Paz of Bolivia,
where four or five of our players were almost unable to play
because they couldn't adjust to the change," Traverso explained.
</P>
<P>
Hoffman said that the team had always been treated cordially in
Ecuador and so he didn't foresee any type of problems.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to have a good stay and, especially, a good game.
Regardless of who wins, whether we do or they do, because both
team are after the same thing: a win," Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
"Chile will arrive in Quito on Tuesday, October 3, and we have
yet to decide if we will leave the city on the same day after the
game, or the next morning," the Chilean coach said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
