<HEADLINE> World's Bests Challenge Australia's Fastests for First Olympic Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- As Australia are sure to grab
the first Olympic gold medal in the women's triathlon, the world's
best are cornered to stop the hosts from sweeping the top three in
the curtain-raiser of the Millennium Olympics on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Australian women filled the first five places in last year's
World Championships and have won eight of the last nine world
titles, and the final three quotas for the hosts were alloted to
Michellie Jones, Nicole Hackett and Loretta Harrop.
</P>
<P>
Top-ranked Jones, 31, has piled her titles over the last 10
years, including back-to-back world titles in 1992-93, and has
been honored as the queen of the sport.
</P>
<P>
Hackett, 21, and Harrop, 25, are the reigning and former
winners of the World Championships. Being fearsome swimmers, both
are expected to line up side by side to open up a sustainable lead
going into the run.
</P>
<P>
"We all know how many people watch the Olympics and it's
fantastic for our sport to open up the Games," said Jones.
</P>
<P>
Challenging the sure bets from the hosts are another 45 world-
class athletes, paced by the American triple Jennifer Gutierrez,
Sheila Taormina and Joanna Zeiger as Taormina is the member of the
U.S. swimming champion team in Atlanta four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Swiss pair Magali Messmer and Brigitte McMahon and Canada's
Sharon Donnelly are likely to challenge the hosts on the bikes,
while Carol Montgomery of Canada, runner-up in the world
championship, is surely the best runner in the field.
</P>
<P>
Montgomery is confident of outracing the Australians if she can
stay reasonably in touch, saying that "if I'm in touch then I hope
I can reel them in." 
</P>
