<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Officials Link Blast to Soeharto Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Speculation mounted here that
supporters of Indonesia's former President Soeharto might be
behind the car bombing and fire at the Jakarta Stock Exchange
Wednesday which killed 15 people on site.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid Thursday demanded quick arrests of
those responsible for the incident, even if it meant hauling in
high-profile individuals and military personnel, The Indonesian
Observer daily Friday reported.
</P>
<P>
"I want the police chief and the attorney general not to
hesitate to act against suspects regardless of their position or
status,"Cabinet Secretary Marsilam Simanjuntak quoted Wahid as
saying during a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
"There are no sacred cows in this country," the president
reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Marzuki Darusman said Wahid ordered the
military commander to join the police investigation. He complained
that investigators were being frustrated by certain members of the
Indonesian Defense Forces (TNI).
</P>
<P>
Bombings have coincided with every major stage of the
investigation of Soeharto, but no arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
A bomb exploded in a bus just before Soeharto's case went
before the court two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Police said a military-type explosive, similar to that used in
another car bombing at the Philippine ambassador's house in
Jakarta on August 1, had caused Wednesday's blast. But no positive
linking has been found between the two fatal attacks.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's blast rocked the capital's downtown financial
district just a day before a court resumed hearings on corruption
charges against Soeharto, who ruled Indonesia with military
support for 32 years until violent demonstrations forced him out
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"It may be linked to the trial of Soeharto," said Coordinating
Minister for Economy Rizal Ramli.
</P>
<P>
After briefing the cabinet on Thursday, National Police chief
Gen.Rusdihardjo described the attack as the work of "professionals.
" He downplayed suggestions that international terrorists were
involved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several office buildings in Jakarta and the second
biggest city of Surabaya received bomb threats Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
