<DOCNO> XIE20000915.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached by Italian Government, Truckers Averts Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deal, agreed with the Transport Ministry and the fuel
companies after long talks will give truckers new fuel discounts
and prevent the kind of chaos that has plagued Britain, France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
In those countries truckers have blockaded refineries and other
major industrial hubs in protest at high fuel costs caused by the
soaring U.S. dollar and the recent surge in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The deal, said Italian Transport Minister Pierluigi Bersani, is
"first of all reasonable and satisfies everyone's demands."
</P>
<P>
The deal will enable Bersani to go to a European Union
transport ministers' meeting in Brussels next Wednesday with an
example of how such disputes can be settled.
</P>
<P>
The accord is in four points, namely, 1) immediate monitoring
and prompt resolution of bureaucratic problems holding back the
rationalization of the Italian fuel distribution system; 2) a cut
in the duty on diesel fuel for haulier using trucks heavier than 3.
5 tons, backdated to September 1 and lasting until the end of the
year, and equal to 120 lire per liter; 3) starting talks to see
whether tax breaks lined up under a carbon-tax law can be speeded
up and; 4) a further tax break on the income of truckers with
vehicles weighing more than 3.5 tons.
</P>
<P>
Bersani also invited the fuel companies to see how fast they
can start bringing down the price of diesel. The first assessment
of this will take place on October 2.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister said he was ready to take further
measures, depending on how the markets go.
</P>
<P>
The Italian truckers' association Cuna on Friday said it had
called a meeting of all European Union hauliers to advertise what
they see as a ground-breaking deal reached with the Italian
government.
</P>
<P>
The truckers' summit will take place in Brussels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cuna said the meeting would examine the crisis that has hit the
trucking sector because of the high cost of diesel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
