<HEADLINE> Fuel Supplies Returning to UK Petrol Stations. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The British government said on
Friday that some 25 percent of the country's 13,000 petrol
stations should have fuel by the end of Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the number of designated fuel stations
was increased from 2,500 to 3,300 -- 298 of which were for
essential users only .
</P>
<P>
But motorists were still being warned they could still face a
wait of up to two weeks for petrol, despite the lifting of nearly
all the blockades at UK refineries on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police were urging motorists to fill up only if the need is
urgent, as lengthy queues develop outside petrol stations.
</P>
<P>
Scottish motorists were still waiting for fuel supplies to get
back to normal, with queues outside many filling stations.
</P>
<P>
There was a patchy picture across the country as oil bosses
predicted 1,200 tankers would leave the Grangemouth oil refinery
by midnight, with 2,500 expected to have made deliveries by Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
In Edinburgh, Glasgow, Tayside and the north-east, many pumps
remained dry and queues were still long on many forecourts,
although several councils were ending their emergency procedures.
</P>
<P>
Despite the end of the crisis, police in Dumfries and Galloway
warned farmers and hauliers were planning a protest on the A75
route Saturday between Castle Douglas and Dumfries.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of slow-moving vehicles was expected to move along the
road, which links Irish ferry ports to England on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Scottish Executive said the crisis should
be over by Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Normality of fuel distribution in Scotland should be close to
being achieved at the beginning of the week," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
