<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Makes Great Progress in Health Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
made great strides in the health sector since the country attained
independence in 1980, with at least 85 percent of the population
now living within eight kilometers of health facilities.
</P>
<P>
At independence Zimbabwe inherited a health system
characterized by gross inequalities in the distribution of
resources according to race, said the country's Health and Child
Welfare Ministry in its quarterly magazine "Lifelines" released
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But with its new policies of equitable distribution, the
government has constructed and rehabilitated about 250 rural
centers, with hospitals increased from 43 to 60 and bed capacity
from 12,603 to 18,845, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said 25 new district hospitals have been constructed making
it possible for the majority of the people to have a health
facility within walking distance.
</P>
<P>
"In 1990/91, Zimbabwe spent more capital on health than any
other sub-Saharan country except Botswana," it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, Zimbabwe has been one of the most
successful countries in the world in combating malnutrition among
children and one of the first countries in the world to establish
an effective transfusion blood safety surveillance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
