<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thomson Announces Another Multimedia Alliance in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"This is a merger with a tremendous partner in which the sum of
the parts is going to be vastly larger than the parts," said Ken
Thomson, chairman of the Toronto-based Thomson Corp., which has
owned one of the country's leading newspapers, the Globe and Mail,
for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Jean Monty, chairman of BCE Inc., said that the alliance will
be able to provide Canadian consumers more quickly with more
information and more variety on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"The journalistic depth of Canada's national newspaper, the
Globe and Mail, coupled with Canada's leading television network,
CTV, and the leading Internet sites like sympatico.ca and
globeandmail.com, give us all the elements to create made-in-
Canada multimedia services that are second to none," said the BCE
chairman.
</P>
<P>
The alliance will be 70.1 percent owned by BCE, which will
contribute properties including CTV and its 71 percent interest in
Internet site Sympatico-Lycos.
</P>
<P>
Thomson will possess 20 percent of the new company by offering
its flagship newspaper the Globe and Mail and other contributions.
</P>
<P>
The other 9.9 percent will go to the Thomson family's
Woodbridge Co., which will in turn contribute 385 million Canadian
dollars (about 259 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This is a third multimedia venture announced since July, when
the Winnipeg-based CanWest Global Communications offered 3.5
billion Canadian dollars (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) to
acquire more than 200 Hollinger publications in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Montreal publisher Quebecor Inc. took over
cable TV company Group Videotron at a price of 4.9 billion
Canadian dollars (about 3.3 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
