<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell
sharply Friday amid worries about corporate earnings and on profit-
taking despite a new proof of tame inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 160.47 at 10,927.
06 points. The blue chip stock index fell 94.71 Thursday and 51.05
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The technology
heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 78.63 at 3,835.23 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 15.06 at 1,465.81.
</P>
<P>
Stocks plunged after the wireless communications company
Anadigics warned that its earnings in the second half of the year
would not meet expectations because of the lower demand for its
products. The fresh warning added to investors' worries about
corporate profits in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The market has been hit in the past week, when a number of
companies said their earnings in the third quarter would be lower
than expectations in the slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates for six times in
the past 15 months in a pre-emptive move to cool off the economy
and keep inflation under control. But higher rates and the slowing
economy would increase costs and slow demands for corporate
products, presenting a threat to companies for their earnings.
</P>
<P>
Stocks were also dragged lower as investors cashed out of some
tech stocks to lock in profits from a previous rally. Software
maker Oracle was lower a day after investors pushed its price
higher on upbeat speculation about its earnings.
</P>
<P>
A government report on the falling consumer prices did not
inspire the market. The Labor Department reported that consumer
prices fell in August for the first time in 14 years, showing a
new proof that inflation remains tame after six hikes in rates.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.00 at 669.42 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 8.33 at 530.88. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 5.37 at 971.86.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,751 down, 1,125 up and 473
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.22 billion shares from 1.00 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
