<HEADLINE> Gore Promotes Education Plan in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore went to a traditionally black
college here on Friday to promote his education plan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to about 1,600 students, teachers and lawmakers at
Howard University, Vice President Gore said that he wants to hire
100,000 new public school teachers to reduce class sizes, give
bonuses to teachers and offer paid leave to teachers for
professional development.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would allow families a tax deduction and take
other measures to make college education more affordable in the
United States if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
Gore, capping a week of campaigning for education reform on
Friday, called for an education system that treats teachers as
professionals.
</P>
<P>
"Education has to be the No.1 priority for this generation,"
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gore's Republican rival George W. Bush campaigned in
California, hoping to gain some ground in the biggest state in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He pushed his education ideas by reading with schoolchildren at
an elementary school and also met with veterans at a park in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
With less than two months to go to election day, the majority
of polls show Gore slightly ahead or even with Bush.  
</P>
</TEXT>
